00:00:22.516 --> 00:00:25.840
PROFESSOR: OK, welcome
everyone.

00:00:25.840 --> 00:00:28.870
It's 8:05, well, 9:05.

00:00:28.870 --> 00:00:31.680
So today's lecture and
discussion is about how to

00:00:31.680 --> 00:00:35.800
make good problems, whether
it's on homework problems,

00:00:35.800 --> 00:00:38.670
exams, even problems in class.

00:00:38.670 --> 00:00:41.530
Its general principles that
you can use constructing

00:00:41.530 --> 00:00:45.710
questions that you ask, so
problems broadly conceived.

00:00:45.710 --> 00:00:49.450
Now why problems?

00:00:49.450 --> 00:00:53.640
So problems are, I think, one
of the central ways of

00:00:53.640 --> 00:00:56.010
thinking about teaching.

00:00:56.010 --> 00:01:02.940
And I'll show you how problems
fit into the grand scheme of

00:01:02.940 --> 00:01:09.395
this course, of rethinking all
the aspects of teaching.

00:01:14.580 --> 00:01:17.490
So one way that I like to think
about teaching is called

00:01:17.490 --> 00:01:18.410
backward design.

00:01:18.410 --> 00:01:21.600
So this is a way of designing a
whole course, could even be

00:01:21.600 --> 00:01:22.780
for a curriculum.

00:01:22.780 --> 00:01:25.840
And doing problems is
one aspect of that.

00:01:35.810 --> 00:01:37.750
So why is it called
backward design?

00:01:37.750 --> 00:01:39.530
Well, it's backward from
the usual way.

00:01:39.530 --> 00:01:41.960
So I'll show you what backward
is and then show you what the

00:01:41.960 --> 00:01:43.210
usual way is.

00:01:50.360 --> 00:01:53.950
So in backward design the
highest-level thing you figure

00:01:53.950 --> 00:01:56.160
out-- not necessarily the first
thing you figure out,

00:01:56.160 --> 00:01:58.380
but the highest level thing--
is your course goals.

00:02:01.070 --> 00:02:05.820
And that then feeds to OK, if
those are your course goals

00:02:05.820 --> 00:02:09.509
how do you know whether students
have reached them?

00:02:09.509 --> 00:02:10.759
And that's problems.

00:02:13.560 --> 00:02:18.010
Problems, tasks, projects,
whatever it may be, things

00:02:18.010 --> 00:02:19.260
that students are going to do.

00:02:21.600 --> 00:02:24.630
And so generally speaking,
things to do.

00:02:24.630 --> 00:02:31.850
And then given that you've
operationalized the goals in

00:02:31.850 --> 00:02:35.910
these problems what are you
going to do in class, so that

00:02:35.910 --> 00:02:38.500
students actually are able to
do these kind of things?

00:02:44.760 --> 00:02:48.210
OK, so that is backward
design because the

00:02:48.210 --> 00:02:50.030
usual way is the following.

00:02:50.030 --> 00:02:52.280
You say, OK, well, you have
a bunch of lecture notes.

00:02:52.280 --> 00:02:53.030
Where do you have those?

00:02:53.030 --> 00:02:54.950
Well, either the last person
who taught the course gives

00:02:54.950 --> 00:02:56.220
you their lecture notes.

00:02:56.220 --> 00:02:58.990
Or you just take the standard
book in the subject and you

00:02:58.990 --> 00:03:03.070
just do the lectures one per
chapter or one week per

00:03:03.070 --> 00:03:04.130
chapter, something like that.

00:03:04.130 --> 00:03:05.420
And you just go through
in the order.

00:03:05.420 --> 00:03:08.180
So in the usual way you
start with this.

00:03:08.180 --> 00:03:10.980
And then you think oh, whoops,
oh yeah, I've got to make some

00:03:10.980 --> 00:03:12.930
problem sets.

00:03:12.930 --> 00:03:14.020
And oh, some exams.

00:03:14.020 --> 00:03:16.200
Well, what have we done this
last couple weeks?

00:03:16.200 --> 00:03:18.060
OK, that's what we're
going to do.

00:03:18.060 --> 00:03:20.100
So the usual way is you
start with here.

00:03:20.100 --> 00:03:21.000
And then you get here.

00:03:21.000 --> 00:03:22.830
And you somehow never
get here.

00:03:22.830 --> 00:03:24.570
The course goals are,
basically, to

00:03:24.570 --> 00:03:26.670
get through the book.

00:03:26.670 --> 00:03:26.850
Right?

00:03:26.850 --> 00:03:28.070
That's the implicit
course goal.

00:03:28.070 --> 00:03:29.820
But it's never explicitly
planned.

00:03:29.820 --> 00:03:32.490
So that's a terrible way,
but the normal way

00:03:32.490 --> 00:03:33.420
of designing a course.

00:03:33.420 --> 00:03:35.490
So this is backward design.

00:03:35.490 --> 00:03:41.880
So this is due to Wiggins
and McTighe.

00:03:49.950 --> 00:03:53.530
OK, so here we're going to
be discussing this today.

00:03:57.180 --> 00:03:58.910
So we're doing this first.

00:03:58.910 --> 00:04:01.030
And then the next session
is this one.

00:04:01.030 --> 00:04:03.300
And I think the session after
that is, what do you do in

00:04:03.300 --> 00:04:05.700
class, interactive teaching
and things like that.

00:04:05.700 --> 00:04:07.860
So why am I doing it
in this order?

00:04:07.860 --> 00:04:10.730
Well, in the levels of
abstraction these

00:04:10.730 --> 00:04:12.550
are the most abstract.

00:04:12.550 --> 00:04:16.530
And this is the most concrete,
OK, what question I'm going to

00:04:16.530 --> 00:04:18.600
ask students in class now.

00:04:18.600 --> 00:04:20.920
And this is things like goals.

00:04:20.920 --> 00:04:22.790
I want them to really understand
conservation.

00:04:22.790 --> 00:04:23.980
They're really high level.

00:04:23.980 --> 00:04:28.600
So I think if you start here, by
trying to figure out course

00:04:28.600 --> 00:04:31.780
goals, I haven't found that
works very well for me because

00:04:31.780 --> 00:04:33.050
it's too high level.

00:04:33.050 --> 00:04:36.560
I can't think about course goals
in absence of actual

00:04:36.560 --> 00:04:38.670
problems and things I want
students to be able to do.

00:04:38.670 --> 00:04:43.830
So this has the right level
between concrete and abstract.

00:04:43.830 --> 00:04:46.390
So it's actually where
I start my thinking.

00:04:46.390 --> 00:04:49.370
Now, you may actually find you
want to start somewhere else

00:04:49.370 --> 00:04:51.400
on the continuum.

00:04:51.400 --> 00:04:54.200
But this is what I found
works quite well.

00:04:54.200 --> 00:04:58.260
You start here, you
operationalize what your goals

00:04:58.260 --> 00:05:00.140
are in the problems that you
think are interesting.

00:05:00.140 --> 00:05:01.580
And then you look
at the problems.

00:05:01.580 --> 00:05:03.980
And that sort of gives you an
idea of the course goals.

00:05:03.980 --> 00:05:05.740
And then you think about
the course goals.

00:05:05.740 --> 00:05:07.090
And that helps you think
of problems.

00:05:07.090 --> 00:05:08.580
But I start here.

00:05:08.580 --> 00:05:12.330
And then, once I have things
like that, then class time is

00:05:12.330 --> 00:05:13.750
actually much easier to plan.

00:05:13.750 --> 00:05:17.030
Because class often is going
to be problems like this,

00:05:17.030 --> 00:05:18.550
related to this,
maybe shorter.

00:05:18.550 --> 00:05:22.120
But it's easier to plan
here after that.

00:05:22.120 --> 00:05:24.400
Whereas we start here, you
don't know, you're

00:05:24.400 --> 00:05:25.630
back in the old way.

00:05:25.630 --> 00:05:26.910
So I don't want to start here.

00:05:26.910 --> 00:05:28.430
This is too abstract,
so I start here.

00:05:28.430 --> 00:05:30.160
So that's why we're
doing this now.

00:05:30.160 --> 00:05:32.970
And then next week we're
going to do this one.

00:05:39.444 --> 00:05:39.942
Question?

00:05:39.942 --> 00:05:41.796
AUDIENCE: So when you say
that you're setting

00:05:41.796 --> 00:05:42.510
goals for your class--

00:05:42.510 --> 00:05:43.470
PROFESSOR: Pardon?

00:05:43.470 --> 00:05:47.160
AUDIENCE: So if you say that,
basically, setting the goals

00:05:47.160 --> 00:05:50.303
for your class, or for
your own course.

00:05:50.303 --> 00:05:52.768
So when you design your course,
basically you write

00:05:52.768 --> 00:05:56.219
out some kind of goals
you want to reach?

00:05:56.219 --> 00:05:57.698
So how do you then
do the problem?

00:05:57.698 --> 00:06:00.590
Do you go in detail
before you've even

00:06:00.590 --> 00:06:01.960
started the whole class?

00:06:01.960 --> 00:06:04.185
Or do you do it that on
a week-to-week basis?

00:06:04.185 --> 00:06:06.000
PROFESSOR: Oh, what do
I tell the students

00:06:06.000 --> 00:06:06.980
about the course goals?

00:06:06.980 --> 00:06:09.932
AUDIENCE: Yeah, I mean, if you
say, OK, basically, you have

00:06:09.932 --> 00:06:14.106
your goals and then you
design problems so you

00:06:14.106 --> 00:06:14.941
can reach the goals?

00:06:14.941 --> 00:06:19.300
But then do you also design
these problems before you even

00:06:19.300 --> 00:06:20.952
start the whole lecture?

00:06:20.952 --> 00:06:22.445
The whole semester?

00:06:22.445 --> 00:06:26.500
PROFESSOR: Oh, well,
it's pretty rough.

00:06:26.500 --> 00:06:31.030
I mean, usually the first time
you teach the thing it's too

00:06:31.030 --> 00:06:32.070
abstract to design--

00:06:32.070 --> 00:06:32.870
I find--

00:06:32.870 --> 00:06:35.110
everything in advance.

00:06:35.110 --> 00:06:39.400
Maybe that's my extrovert
nature, which is that I find

00:06:39.400 --> 00:06:42.730
it hard to design things for
people I don't know.

00:06:42.730 --> 00:06:47.190
If I don't know the audience I
don't even know what to say.

00:06:47.190 --> 00:06:50.300
So I want to actually teach the
course one time at least.

00:06:50.300 --> 00:06:53.440
So then the audience becomes
concrete for me.

00:06:53.440 --> 00:06:56.260
So really, the first time
through the course nothing is

00:06:56.260 --> 00:06:56.950
ever ideal.

00:06:56.950 --> 00:06:59.370
And you're doing everything
on the fly.

00:06:59.370 --> 00:07:02.610
But the second time through the
course, you can actually,

00:07:02.610 --> 00:07:04.650
basically, make all the problems
ahead of time.

00:07:04.650 --> 00:07:06.930
So the second time through the
course you actually refine

00:07:06.930 --> 00:07:09.165
your goals and your
problems together.

00:07:13.310 --> 00:07:16.653
So that shows you the structure
of where we are and

00:07:16.653 --> 00:07:17.930
where we're going to
go and then later.

00:07:17.930 --> 00:07:20.040
So this is two weeks from now.

00:07:22.810 --> 00:07:24.060
Today, here.

00:07:26.530 --> 00:07:29.600
So how do you make problems?

00:07:29.600 --> 00:07:36.710
Well, the fundamental principle
is, again, deduced

00:07:36.710 --> 00:07:41.140
by induction from what happens
with regular problems.

00:07:41.140 --> 00:07:46.860
So if you remember, I gave you
an example earlier of the

00:07:46.860 --> 00:07:49.470
results of standard
problem solving.

00:07:49.470 --> 00:07:51.640
And I'll just remind you that
we're putting up the

00:07:51.640 --> 00:07:52.890
percentages again.

00:08:06.550 --> 00:08:10.770
OK, so after doing lots
and lots of standard

00:08:10.770 --> 00:08:13.880
multiplication problems,
students were--

00:08:13.880 --> 00:08:16.310
if you remember-- unable to
do the following problem.

00:08:24.850 --> 00:08:28.360
So these 13-year-Olds and
17-year-Olds were asked to

00:08:28.360 --> 00:08:34.140
estimate 3.04 times 5.3.

00:08:34.140 --> 00:08:35.690
So here were the answers.

00:08:44.039 --> 00:08:47.410
So they were given four
possible answers.

00:08:47.410 --> 00:08:50.670
And they could also
not answer.

00:08:50.670 --> 00:08:51.920
So this is no answer.

00:09:08.540 --> 00:09:12.010
So that's the age 13.

00:09:12.010 --> 00:09:15.090
So of the four possible
answers--

00:09:15.090 --> 00:09:18.690
or let's say no answer is
possible as well-- so five,

00:09:18.690 --> 00:09:24.580
they're 1% over 1/5 will
get the correct answer.

00:09:24.580 --> 00:09:25.765
So that's a bit depressing.

00:09:25.765 --> 00:09:27.355
So you think, oh, OK,
the 17-year-olds

00:09:27.355 --> 00:09:28.605
are going to be better.

00:09:31.350 --> 00:09:34.360
And they are, but they only
have 37% correct.

00:09:38.320 --> 00:09:43.650
OK, so here is a serious
problem,

00:09:43.650 --> 00:09:46.090
which is rote learning.

00:09:46.090 --> 00:09:48.090
And that's the fundamental
thing to

00:09:48.090 --> 00:09:50.690
avoid when doing problems.

00:09:50.690 --> 00:09:54.020
So these students-- especially
the 17-year-olds--

00:09:54.020 --> 00:09:56.470
were actually perfectly capable
of doing exactly

00:09:56.470 --> 00:09:56.805
multiplication.

00:09:56.805 --> 00:09:59.410
So on the same test they were
asked questions like multiply

00:09:59.410 --> 00:10:04.420
2.7 by 8.32 and given just empty
space on the page to

00:10:04.420 --> 00:10:05.700
multiply it out.

00:10:05.700 --> 00:10:07.380
About 80% did it right.

00:10:07.380 --> 00:10:10.160
So it's not that they don't
know how to multiply.

00:10:10.160 --> 00:10:13.510
They just don't know what
multiplication means, which is

00:10:13.510 --> 00:10:15.720
a far more serious problem.

00:10:15.720 --> 00:10:18.870
I'd rather they knew what
multiplication meant and

00:10:18.870 --> 00:10:21.300
didn't really understand,
didn't

00:10:21.300 --> 00:10:22.420
really know how to multiply.

00:10:22.420 --> 00:10:24.950
Because the algorithm you can
teach them later if they

00:10:24.950 --> 00:10:26.280
understand what it means.

00:10:26.280 --> 00:10:28.990
But if they don't even
understand what it means that

00:10:28.990 --> 00:10:31.270
basically it's 3 times 5, so
it's got to be somewhere

00:10:31.270 --> 00:10:33.920
around 16, they don't understand
what multiplication

00:10:33.920 --> 00:10:36.050
means or the number
system means.

00:10:36.050 --> 00:10:37.880
That's a far more
serious problem.

00:10:37.880 --> 00:10:41.830
And that's produced by the
traditional kind of problems.

00:10:41.830 --> 00:10:44.730
The traditional kinds of
problems are, generally

00:10:44.730 --> 00:10:48.140
speaking, too low level
and can be solved,

00:10:48.140 --> 00:10:49.550
to easily, by rote.

00:10:49.550 --> 00:10:51.890
Even the complicated traditional
problems can

00:10:51.890 --> 00:10:55.710
eventually be turned
into rote learning,

00:10:55.710 --> 00:10:56.880
and that's the danger.

00:10:56.880 --> 00:11:01.490
So the main goal in making
good problems is--

00:11:01.490 --> 00:11:02.030
I would say--

00:11:02.030 --> 00:11:06.190
how to make problems that
fight rote learning.

00:11:06.190 --> 00:11:06.360
OK?

00:11:06.360 --> 00:11:09.560
That produce long-lasting
actual conceptual

00:11:09.560 --> 00:11:12.090
understanding along with
whatever else you're trying to

00:11:12.090 --> 00:11:13.500
produce and teach.

00:11:13.500 --> 00:11:16.030
But really, fight the rote
learning because that is the

00:11:16.030 --> 00:11:18.730
fundamental problem.

00:11:18.730 --> 00:11:25.110
So a way of thinking about
this is to categorize the

00:11:25.110 --> 00:11:28.260
levels of thinking that you're
expecting of students when

00:11:28.260 --> 00:11:29.710
you're asking them
to do a problem.

00:11:29.710 --> 00:11:37.060
And for that there is work
from 50 years ago now--

00:11:37.060 --> 00:11:38.440
which is still useful--

00:11:49.530 --> 00:11:53.810
which is Bloom's Taxonomy.

00:11:53.810 --> 00:11:55.990
So Bloom's Taxonomy--

00:11:55.990 --> 00:11:56.960
let's see, when was it?

00:11:56.960 --> 00:12:02.210
I think it was 1956.

00:12:02.210 --> 00:12:03.300
I think it was '56.

00:12:03.300 --> 00:12:07.420
I'll put a handout on the
website for you which

00:12:07.420 --> 00:12:08.930
summarizes in one page.

00:12:08.930 --> 00:12:11.690
But I'll summarize it
even shorter here.

00:12:14.700 --> 00:12:17.050
So what is it a taxonomy of?

00:12:17.050 --> 00:12:19.530
Well, when you read the title
the book, it's Bloom's

00:12:19.530 --> 00:12:23.440
Taxonomy of Educational
Objectives.

00:12:23.440 --> 00:12:25.430
And it's not really clear if
that's going to be useful for

00:12:25.430 --> 00:12:26.040
anything at all.

00:12:26.040 --> 00:12:27.630
Because you think, what
the hell is that?

00:12:27.630 --> 00:12:31.690
So the shortest way of
understanding it is that it's

00:12:31.690 --> 00:12:33.290
six levels.

00:12:33.290 --> 00:12:39.980
And each level is higher than
the one previous to it in

00:12:39.980 --> 00:12:44.590
terms of the level of thought
required of a student.

00:12:44.590 --> 00:12:46.010
So it's not really
a strict order.

00:12:46.010 --> 00:12:49.810
You can have really hard
questions that seem to be low

00:12:49.810 --> 00:12:51.940
level just because they address
misconceptions.

00:12:51.940 --> 00:12:54.190
But generally speaking,
it's a rough order.

00:12:54.190 --> 00:13:02.950
So the order is knowledge
questions.

00:13:02.950 --> 00:13:08.360
Those are things like define,
name, state, list, You know,

00:13:08.360 --> 00:13:10.150
it's basically almost rote.

00:13:10.150 --> 00:13:13.340
I mean, these are the kind of
problems that everyone would

00:13:13.340 --> 00:13:16.850
agree are rote, state
the definition of

00:13:16.850 --> 00:13:18.100
Newton's Second Law.

00:13:28.880 --> 00:13:30.950
The second is comprehension.

00:13:30.950 --> 00:13:33.650
So that's sort of like
knowledge but

00:13:33.650 --> 00:13:35.432
it's a higher level.

00:13:35.432 --> 00:13:39.110
So that's being able to grasp
the meaning of the material,

00:13:39.110 --> 00:13:41.170
not just recite the facts.

00:13:43.750 --> 00:13:46.040
But generally, that doesn't
include the idea of being able

00:13:46.040 --> 00:13:48.170
to transfer it to
new situations.

00:13:48.170 --> 00:13:50.008
That's where application
comes.

00:13:53.500 --> 00:13:57.410
So can you apply the material
to something?

00:13:57.410 --> 00:14:04.660
For example, often compute,
demonstrate, show that, those

00:14:04.660 --> 00:14:07.210
are typical verbs that
are used when you

00:14:07.210 --> 00:14:08.460
have application questions.

00:14:13.620 --> 00:14:16.600
The next level is analysis.

00:14:16.600 --> 00:14:19.600
So that's really trying to
understand the structure of

00:14:19.600 --> 00:14:21.080
the material.

00:14:21.080 --> 00:14:28.240
So things like diagram,
differentiate, infer, outline,

00:14:28.240 --> 00:14:32.270
point out, identify,
distinguish, discriminate, all

00:14:32.270 --> 00:14:35.365
those kinds of verbs com into
analysis kinds of questions.

00:14:42.140 --> 00:14:44.400
Synthesis--

00:14:44.400 --> 00:14:47.640
so this is breaking
things apart.

00:14:47.640 --> 00:14:49.210
This is the ability
to put things back

00:14:49.210 --> 00:14:51.600
together in new ways.

00:14:51.600 --> 00:14:51.840
OK?

00:14:51.840 --> 00:14:57.980
So design, explain, categorize,
create, revise,

00:14:57.980 --> 00:15:00.915
rewrite, reorganize, devise.

00:15:10.090 --> 00:15:13.460
And the highest level
is evaluation.

00:15:13.460 --> 00:15:19.950
So judging the value of
material, for what purposes is

00:15:19.950 --> 00:15:23.450
this good versus that good?

00:15:23.450 --> 00:15:28.680
Explain, contrast, summarize,
support, recommend, evaluate,

00:15:28.680 --> 00:15:31.040
criticize, appraise,
so generally

00:15:31.040 --> 00:15:32.170
