00:18:38.820 --> 00:18:41.530
OK, this next one is
an application.

00:18:41.530 --> 00:18:44.660
It turns out to be, actually,
quite a hard application.

00:18:44.660 --> 00:18:45.910
But it's still an application.

00:18:54.660 --> 00:18:57.310
So it's to apply Newton's second
and third law to show

00:18:57.310 --> 00:19:03.640
the following, which the
following is suppose I have a

00:19:03.640 --> 00:19:07.080
piece of chalk in my hand and
I stand on a weighing scale.

00:19:07.080 --> 00:19:09.600
I want the students to show that
the weight that the scale

00:19:09.600 --> 00:19:12.560
reads is equal to the sum of
the two individual weights.

00:19:12.560 --> 00:19:14.360
So I weigh myself.

00:19:14.360 --> 00:19:15.930
And then I put the chalk
on the scale.

00:19:15.930 --> 00:19:17.150
And I add up those
two weights.

00:19:17.150 --> 00:19:18.780
And that should be the
same as when I hold

00:19:18.780 --> 00:19:20.290
the chalk in my hand.

00:19:20.290 --> 00:19:20.530
OK?

00:19:20.530 --> 00:19:23.035
So I'll diagram that as--

00:19:35.430 --> 00:19:45.160
OK, so that's me plus chalk
equals me plus chalk.

00:19:45.160 --> 00:19:46.410
So this is a scale.

00:19:48.860 --> 00:19:49.300
OK?

00:19:49.300 --> 00:19:50.970
So there is the piece
of chalk.

00:19:50.970 --> 00:19:57.060
So now this is an example of
