though it's kind of high up on

00:20:00.100 --> 00:20:03.590
the Bloom's list, so towards
the lower end.

00:20:03.590 --> 00:20:05.680
Because this is a serious
misconception

00:20:05.680 --> 00:20:06.710
that students have.

00:20:06.710 --> 00:20:09.110
Newton's second and Newton's
third law, people are

00:20:09.110 --> 00:20:11.390
completely confused about,
you'll find.

00:20:11.390 --> 00:20:15.250
They don't know when
to use which.

00:20:15.250 --> 00:20:18.890
And they think any time two
forces are equal it's sort of

00:20:18.890 --> 00:20:21.150
50-50, whether it's because of
Newton's third law or Newton's

00:20:21.150 --> 00:20:22.790
second law.

00:20:22.790 --> 00:20:25.210
So this-- if you're addressing
misconceptions--

00:20:25.210 --> 00:20:28.320
makes the problem, actually,
all the much harder.

00:20:33.480 --> 00:20:35.060
So at analysis--

00:20:35.060 --> 00:20:37.040
so the analysis comes out--
oh, question sorry.

00:20:37.040 --> 00:20:38.381
AUDIENCE: What are Newton's
second and third laws?

00:20:38.381 --> 00:20:39.950
PROFESSOR: Ah, fair question.

00:20:39.950 --> 00:20:52.120
So Newton's Second Law says
force equals mass times

00:20:52.120 --> 00:20:53.530
acceleration.

00:20:53.530 --> 00:20:57.140
Third law is--

00:20:57.140 --> 00:21:00.010
the way it's usually stated,
which it's terrible--

00:21:05.470 --> 00:21:07.870
action equals reaction.

00:21:07.870 --> 00:21:11.840
Or for every action there's an
equal and opposite reaction.

00:21:11.840 --> 00:21:13.690
Oh, which reminds me, one of
the questions from before,

00:21:13.690 --> 00:21:15.660
which is what name
would I give?

00:21:15.660 --> 00:21:18.560
Because I said I slagged off the
reaction force as the name

00:21:18.560 --> 00:21:19.970
and the normal force
as a name.

00:21:19.970 --> 00:21:21.800
People ask me, what should
you call it?

00:21:21.800 --> 00:21:23.230
And I actually thought
about that.

00:21:23.230 --> 00:21:25.970
And I think the answer
is contact force.

00:21:25.970 --> 00:21:27.260
Because that tells you
what the thing is.

00:21:27.260 --> 00:21:29.340
It's a force of contact.

00:21:29.340 --> 00:21:32.160
So Newton's third law says
action equals reaction.

00:21:32.160 --> 00:21:36.510
So now, the problem is that
students have, is that

00:21:36.510 --> 00:21:39.840
whenever they see two forces
are equal they assume it's

00:21:39.840 --> 00:21:42.410
because the action
equals reaction.

00:21:42.410 --> 00:21:47.730
Or they think Newton's third
law is the reason for it.

00:21:47.730 --> 00:21:53.450
So for example, the
bouncing-ball question that we

00:21:53.450 --> 00:21:55.100
talked about last time.

00:21:55.100 --> 00:21:57.320
So in the bouncing ball the
question is, when it's

00:21:57.320 --> 00:21:59.480
stationary on the ground what
are the forces on it?

00:21:59.480 --> 00:22:02.550
And they'll often say, well,
there's a weight downwards.

00:22:02.550 --> 00:22:04.560
And there's the force upwards.

00:22:04.560 --> 00:22:07.640
And they'll often say, well, the
force upwards equals the

00:22:07.640 --> 00:22:08.330
weight downwards.

00:22:08.330 --> 00:22:09.800
These are both forces
on the ball because

00:22:09.800 --> 00:22:12.190
action equals reaction.

00:22:12.190 --> 00:22:15.310
And they won't realize that
action and reaction have to be

00:22:15.310 --> 00:22:17.860
on different objects.

00:22:17.860 --> 00:22:18.130
OK?

00:22:18.130 --> 00:22:21.920
So they're fundamentally
confused about the meaning of

00:22:21.920 --> 00:22:24.450
action and reaction, which you
can bring out with the

00:22:24.450 --> 00:22:25.700
following analysis question--

00:22:32.190 --> 00:22:36.740
When two forces are equal in
magnitude how do you tell if

00:22:36.740 --> 00:22:38.440
it's Newton's two
or Newton three?

00:22:41.570 --> 00:22:43.570
So how do you know if it's
Newton two or Newton three?

00:22:43.570 --> 00:22:45.400
So just ask them that.

00:22:45.400 --> 00:22:47.172
Yes, question?

