PROFESSOR: Ah, oh,
OK, interesting.

00:23:02.190 --> 00:23:04.930
So OK, let me actually
explain that one.

00:23:04.930 --> 00:23:07.020
I'll put it over there because
I didn't do the

00:23:07.020 --> 00:23:09.460
boards right over here.

00:23:09.460 --> 00:23:13.580
So that is exactly the issue
brought out by this question.

00:23:13.580 --> 00:23:14.925
And let me show you
the difference.

00:23:19.150 --> 00:23:20.830
And then there was
another question.

00:23:20.830 --> 00:23:22.780
That reminds me of another whole
set of questions from

00:23:22.780 --> 00:23:26.540
the sheets, which was
how do you develop

00:23:26.540 --> 00:23:29.440
your physics intuition?

00:23:29.440 --> 00:23:31.810
So let me answer that
in a moment.

00:23:31.810 --> 00:23:33.820
After this and then we'll
have a break.

00:23:33.820 --> 00:23:36.975
OK, so the bouncing-ball
question--

00:23:40.720 --> 00:23:41.990
actually let's not do
the bouncing ball.

00:23:41.990 --> 00:23:48.630
Let's just do an object
sitting on the ground.

00:23:52.446 --> 00:23:56.000
Oh, great, can you
pass them around?

00:23:58.890 --> 00:24:04.060
Oh, Leeann's just coming around
with a handout on

00:24:04.060 --> 00:24:05.413
Bloom's Taxonomy.

00:24:05.413 --> 00:24:08.900
And let's see, I'll do these
after the break.

00:24:08.900 --> 00:24:11.140
OK, suppose you have this object
sitting on the ground

00:24:11.140 --> 00:24:12.920
and it has Mass m.

00:24:12.920 --> 00:24:14.990
OK, let's look at what
the forces on it are.

00:24:14.990 --> 00:24:18.580
Well, there's mg down--

00:24:18.580 --> 00:24:25.370
and actually, in this case, the
contact force, our normal

00:24:25.370 --> 00:24:28.830
force is equal to mg.

00:24:28.830 --> 00:24:32.690
OK, so now the question is, are
these two equal because of

00:24:32.690 --> 00:24:34.490
Newton's Second Law or
Newton's third law?

00:24:34.490 --> 00:24:36.430
That's what this
question asks.

00:24:36.430 --> 00:24:37.760
So it's actually worth
understanding

00:24:37.760 --> 00:24:40.420
the difference here.

00:24:40.420 --> 00:24:45.560
So these guys are equal
because a equals 0.

00:24:45.560 --> 00:24:49.280
So this thing's just sitting
on the ground, a equals 0.

00:24:49.280 --> 00:24:53.810
So the net force is
0, so these two

00:24:53.810 --> 00:24:55.780
forces have to cancel.

00:24:55.780 --> 00:24:59.230
OK, so that's Newton's
Second Law.

00:25:08.100 --> 00:25:10.980
So then the question is, where
does Newton's Third Law show

00:25:10.980 --> 00:25:11.990
up in this?

00:25:11.990 --> 00:25:14.970
Ah, Newton's Third Law
shows up here.

00:25:18.600 --> 00:25:20.690
Here is the Earth.

00:25:20.690 --> 00:25:23.090
And here is your object.

00:25:23.090 --> 00:25:25.966
Let's just separate them just so
you can see them separate,

00:25:25.966 --> 00:25:27.790
although this is sitting
on there.

00:25:27.790 --> 00:25:30.380
So this is mg.

00:25:30.380 --> 00:25:34.140
Well, this is the mg because
of gravity, right?

00:25:34.140 --> 00:25:37.260
The earth gravity is attracted
to mass, m.

00:25:37.260 --> 00:25:40.500
Well, the mass is also attracted
to the earth.

00:25:40.500 --> 00:25:44.585
So what's the force on the
earth from the mass?

00:25:44.585 --> 00:25:45.507
AUDIENCE: mg.

00:25:45.507 --> 00:25:49.020
PROFESSOR: mg, it has to be.

00:25:49.020 --> 00:25:51.460
Now this mg equals that mg.

00:25:51.460 --> 00:25:56.500
Call this f2 and this is f1.

00:25:56.500 --> 00:26:02.970
So f1 equals f2 by Newton's
third law.

00:26:02.970 --> 00:26:05.730
So that's a fundamentally
different set of forces.

00:26:05.730 --> 00:26:08.480
So are equal and opposite.

00:26:08.480 --> 00:26:11.510
They're an action/reaction
pair.

00:26:11.510 --> 00:26:13.650
So what Newton's third
law really says--

00:26:13.650 --> 00:26:16.070
when you understand it-- is that
all forces in the world

00:26:16.070 --> 00:26:18.120
come in pairs.

00:26:18.120 --> 00:26:20.430
So if you ever see one force
you have to hunt around for

00:26:20.430 --> 00:26:22.520
his other half.

00:26:22.520 --> 00:26:24.530
And the other half
here is this.

00:26:24.530 --> 00:26:30.370
So actually, there's another
question you could use for

00:26:30.370 --> 00:26:32.480
Newton's third law.

00:26:32.480 --> 00:26:34.550
So I don't have it
on the list here.

00:26:34.550 --> 00:26:37.980
But I'll ask it right now, which
is suppose someone comes

00:26:37.980 --> 00:26:41.730
to you and proposes the
following gravitational law--

00:26:41.730 --> 00:26:49.980
f gravity equals g m1 squared
m2 over r squared when the g

00:26:49.980 --> 00:26:51.410
is the proper units.

00:26:51.410 --> 00:26:54.230
So m1 squared times m2,
is that a legal

00:26:54.230 --> 00:26:57.220
force law for gravity?

00:26:57.220 --> 00:27:01.200
No, because when you switch m1
and m2 as you're doing here--

00:27:01.200 --> 00:27:03.110
you're switching the mass
and the earth--

00:27:03.110 --> 00:27:05.100
you actually change the force.

00:27:05.100 --> 00:27:07.500
So then this would violate
Newton's third law.

00:27:10.500 --> 00:27:11.000
OK?

00:27:11.000 --> 00:27:13.510
So Newton's third law, it
actually is a constraint on

00:27:13.510 --> 00:27:14.440
the laws of physics.

00:27:14.440 --> 00:27:16.920
It's actually conservation
of momentum.

00:27:16.920 --> 00:27:19.780
And for momentum to be conserved
you can't have any

00:27:19.780 --> 00:27:22.100
arbitrary law of physics
that you want.

00:27:22.100 --> 00:27:24.500
Does that help clarify that?

00:27:24.500 --> 00:27:27.470
AUDIENCE: Come up with a better
set of taxonomy for

00:27:27.470 --> 00:27:30.597
describing it that doesn't lead
people-- it leads people

00:27:30.597 --> 00:27:31.066
into thinking about that.

00:27:31.066 --> 00:27:32.500
PROFESSOR: I know.

00:27:32.500 --> 00:27:32.960
I agree.

00:27:32.960 --> 00:27:34.740
So I think the terms
are very important.

00:27:34.740 --> 00:27:39.030
So that's why don't like this
form, action equals reaction.

00:27:39.030 --> 00:27:43.940
I actually would prefer it were
stated all forces come in

00:27:43.940 --> 00:27:45.860
pairs that are equal
and opposite.

00:27:57.390 --> 00:28:00.580
Right, and language does
have a powerful effect.

00:28:00.580 --> 00:28:00.935
Yes?

