00:29:11.330 --> 00:29:15.970
And here is a very hard evaluate
question, which is

00:29:15.970 --> 00:29:24.180
what, if any, are the limits of
validity of Newton's Second

00:29:24.180 --> 00:29:25.430
and third law?

00:29:35.190 --> 00:29:36.450
So that's, actually, a very

00:29:36.450 --> 00:29:39.440
interesting historical question.

00:29:39.440 --> 00:29:41.710
Interesting historically because
Einstein thought about

00:29:41.710 --> 00:29:43.150
that question.

00:29:43.150 --> 00:29:47.740
He wanted to know whether
Newtonian gravitation and

00:29:47.740 --> 00:29:49.930
special relativity
were compatible.

00:29:49.930 --> 00:29:55.030
And basically, they can't be
because of Newton's third law.

00:29:55.030 --> 00:29:58.380
Because gravity should propagate
with some speed, not

00:29:58.380 --> 00:30:00.230
the speed of light.

00:30:00.230 --> 00:30:02.970
So you can't actually conserve
momentum right away.

00:30:02.970 --> 00:30:05.530
Suppose the sun does
something strange.

00:30:05.530 --> 00:30:07.440
Well, it takes a while
for the earth to

00:30:07.440 --> 00:30:08.900
actually respond to that.

00:30:08.900 --> 00:30:11.300
And it's in that intervening
time Newton's third law seems

00:30:11.300 --> 00:30:12.310
to be violated.

00:30:12.310 --> 00:30:14.310
So Einstein thought very
carefully about that question

00:30:14.310 --> 00:30:16.220
and came up with his theory
of gravitation.

00:30:16.220 --> 00:30:18.160
So this is quite a high-level
question.

00:30:18.160 --> 00:30:21.850
But it's to show the whole range
of things you can ask

00:30:21.850 --> 00:30:24.270
about the second and Newton's
third law as you

