00:45:58.540 --> 00:46:00.010
and where would I put that?

00:46:00.010 --> 00:46:02.400
Eh, interpret is somewhere
like analysis,

00:46:02.400 --> 00:46:03.610
maybe a bit of synthesis.

00:46:03.610 --> 00:46:05.860
But yeah, it's quite
high on the list.

00:46:05.860 --> 00:46:09.770
So interpret, that's another
really key word.

00:46:09.770 --> 00:46:11.930
In fact, it's often
neglected, right?

00:46:11.930 --> 00:46:14.450
We just ask students to
solve the problem.

00:46:14.450 --> 00:46:15.940
And wander, wander, wander.

00:46:15.940 --> 00:46:18.260
They get the thing that
looks like an answer.

00:46:18.260 --> 00:46:20.750
They put a box around
it and they're done.

00:46:20.750 --> 00:46:24.150
But actually, you can massively
increase the level

00:46:24.150 --> 00:46:26.420
of a problem just by adding
to the problem,

00:46:26.420 --> 00:46:28.700
interpret your answer.

00:46:28.700 --> 00:46:31.520
What does it mean, that
that's an eigenvalue?

00:46:31.520 --> 00:46:33.140
And maybe they would say
something like this.

00:46:33.140 --> 00:46:37.690
But even that would be better
than just having done the

00:46:37.690 --> 00:46:39.920
computational procedure and
got an answer out of it.

00:46:42.800 --> 00:46:44.120
Yes, can you tell
me your name?

00:46:44.120 --> 00:46:44.745
AUDIENCE: Ben.

00:46:44.745 --> 00:46:45.700
PROFESSOR: Ben, yes?

00:46:45.700 --> 00:46:49.095
AUDIENCE: I might ask, does
that matrix have any

00:46:49.095 --> 00:46:49.580
eigenvalues?

00:46:49.580 --> 00:46:53.625
PROFESSOR: OK, so yeah, so
let's put it over here.

00:47:02.510 --> 00:47:07.080
Right, so there what you're
doing is you're not presuming.

00:47:07.080 --> 00:47:10.430
You're not key-wording
what they should do.

00:47:10.430 --> 00:47:13.120
When you do this-- especially
if it's a

00:47:13.120 --> 00:47:14.680
linear algebra course--

00:47:14.680 --> 00:47:16.700
they've probably seen a bunch
of things like this.

00:47:16.700 --> 00:47:18.280
Like in a calculus
course, integrate

00:47:18.280 --> 00:47:19.600
these things by parts.

00:47:19.600 --> 00:47:23.040
They just know I have to
integrate by parts, whereas

00:47:23.040 --> 00:47:25.590
here you're at least
one step higher.

00:47:25.590 --> 00:47:27.260
Because they don't know whether
there's an answer to

00:47:27.260 --> 00:47:28.110
the problem or not.

00:47:28.110 --> 00:47:29.990
And they have to think, well,
how do I know if they're

00:47:29.990 --> 00:47:30.550
eigenvalues?

00:47:30.550 --> 00:47:33.800
So there's actually one
intervening level of

00:47:33.800 --> 00:47:36.420
sophistication.

00:47:36.420 --> 00:47:37.470
Other suggestions?

00:47:37.470 --> 00:47:38.763
Yes, Adrian?

00:47:38.763 --> 00:47:43.615
AUDIENCE: Just give them two
numbers and say write a matrix

00:47:43.615 --> 00:47:45.465
that has these as
the eigenvalues?

00:47:45.465 --> 00:47:49.855
PROFESSOR: OK, so let me
continue the list over here.

00:48:00.890 --> 00:48:06.800
OK, so create a matrix which has
the following eigenvalues.

00:48:17.860 --> 00:48:21.410
So say lambda equals
2 comma 3.

00:48:21.410 --> 00:48:27.390
So create a matrix,
create a meaning.

00:48:27.390 --> 00:48:31.200
We're already high up in the
taxonomy toward synthesis.

00:48:31.200 --> 00:48:34.640
And actually, I would even use
a related one, which is--

00:48:48.260 --> 00:48:52.990
so create a real matrix with
eigenvalues i comma minus i.

00:48:52.990 --> 00:48:55.170
So that one, is quite
related to this.

00:48:55.170 --> 00:48:59.190
And this is the answer.

00:48:59.190 --> 00:49:02.910
So it's quite a hard question.

00:49:02.910 --> 00:49:08.240
Even if people can do this and
find i comma minus i, this one

00:49:08.240 --> 00:49:12.190
is very hard because you're
asking to apply a constraint

00:49:12.190 --> 00:49:14.170
that the thing be real.

00:49:14.170 --> 00:49:15.630
So it's not just any matrix.

00:49:15.630 --> 00:49:16.830
But it's that the
thing be real.

00:49:16.830 --> 00:49:18.580
And then you have to really
understand quite a lot about

00:49:18.580 --> 00:49:21.180
matrices to do that.

00:49:21.180 --> 00:49:22.110
Yes, can you tell
me your name?

00:49:22.110 --> 00:49:22.830
AUDIENCE: Scott.

00:49:22.830 --> 00:49:23.230
PROFESSOR: Scott.

00:49:23.230 --> 00:49:26.436
AUDIENCE: So, I was thinking of
a synthesis question which

00:49:26.436 --> 00:49:31.380
would be is after multiplying
the item the eigenvector by

00:49:31.380 --> 00:49:34.352
the matrix how is it rotated?

00:49:34.352 --> 00:49:39.460
PROFESSOR: OK, so what is the
geometric effect on the

00:49:39.460 --> 00:49:42.892
eigenvector of the matrix
on the eigenvector?

00:49:42.892 --> 00:49:45.181
AUDIENCE: Right, but the
question is if they understand

00:49:45.181 --> 00:49:46.635
what an eigenvalue is.

00:49:46.635 --> 00:49:51.090
PROFESSOR: They should be able
to answer that right away.

00:49:51.090 --> 00:49:53.370
Right, but it really tests for
understanding of what the

00:49:53.370 --> 00:49:53.800
meaning is.

00:49:53.800 --> 00:49:57.720
So it's another way of
approaching the question of do

00:49:57.720 --> 00:49:59.185
they understand eigenvalue
means?

00:50:13.880 --> 00:50:16.040
What is the geometric effect
of the matrix on the

00:50:16.040 --> 00:50:18.860
eigenvector?

00:50:18.860 --> 00:50:21.960
And then hopefully, they'll be
able to say well, actually, it

00:50:21.960 --> 00:50:22.740
doesn't rotate it.

00:50:22.740 --> 00:50:23.690
It just scales it.

00:50:23.690 --> 00:50:27.740
And the eigenvalue is the
amount of scaling.

00:50:27.740 --> 00:50:30.640
OK, and that demonstrates
quite a high level of

00:50:30.640 --> 00:50:31.850
understanding too.

00:50:31.850 --> 00:50:35.200
And This is one reason that
oral exams, generally, are

00:50:35.200 --> 00:50:36.830
quite good ways of evaluating.

00:50:36.830 --> 00:50:38.380
Because you can ask these
kind of questions.

00:50:38.380 --> 00:50:41.430
And as soon as you see that they
understand you move on to

00:50:41.430 --> 00:50:42.610
something else.

00:50:42.610 --> 00:50:45.330
Which of the flip side is that's
why oral exams are very

00:50:45.330 --> 00:50:46.990
disconcerting for
the students.

00:50:46.990 --> 00:50:50.100
Because you spend no time on
the things they understand.

00:50:50.100 --> 00:50:50.600
Right?

00:50:50.600 --> 00:50:52.510
So as soon as you know they
understand it, you move on to

00:50:52.510 --> 00:50:53.210
something else.

00:50:53.210 --> 00:50:54.500
So the student just feels
like, what the

00:50:54.500 --> 00:50:55.930
hell happened to me?

00:50:55.930 --> 00:50:56.820
I was doing fine.

00:50:56.820 --> 00:50:58.230
And they asked me about
something else.

00:50:58.230 --> 00:50:59.090
Yeah, that's exactly right.

00:50:59.090 --> 00:51:01.000
That's why they asked you
about something else.

00:51:01.000 --> 00:51:02.920
They knew there was nothing
more here to find out.

00:51:02.920 --> 00:51:05.040
You understood it.

00:51:05.040 --> 00:51:07.720
But that's why oral exams
are such a good way-- so

00:51:07.720 --> 00:51:08.480
efficient--

00:51:08.480 --> 00:51:09.730
for evaluating.

00:51:12.370 --> 00:51:17.810
So in Cambridge we used to do
oral exam interviews for

00:51:17.810 --> 00:51:19.730
admission for undergraduate.

00:51:19.730 --> 00:51:22.280
So people would be admitted
to the major right away.

00:51:22.280 --> 00:51:25.720
So we had two 20-minute
interviews.

00:51:25.720 --> 00:51:27.780
And we found those were much
more reliable than all the

00:51:27.780 --> 00:51:30.440
exams that they did in
high school, the

00:51:30.440 --> 00:51:32.010
equivalent of AP exams.

00:51:32.010 --> 00:51:34.200
Because you could really ask
questions that really probed

00:51:34.200 --> 00:51:37.330
understanding and right away see
what people could do and

00:51:37.330 --> 00:51:39.760
couldn't do.

00:51:39.760 --> 00:51:43.750
So geometric effective of m on e
creating a matrix, so you're

00:51:43.750 --> 00:51:46.650
asking, so what's the
geometric effect?

00:51:46.650 --> 00:51:48.000
It's not just comprehension.

00:51:48.000 --> 00:51:51.507
You're asking them to apply
it and maybe, in a

00:51:51.507 --> 00:51:53.170
bit in a new area.

00:51:53.170 --> 00:51:55.690
They hadn't really thought of
eigenvalues and eigenvectors

00:51:55.690 --> 00:51:56.675
as geometric at all.

00:51:56.675 --> 00:51:58.320
And now, all of sudden, you're
asking them that.

00:51:58.320 --> 00:52:00.700
You're asking them to transfer
their knowledge, which is one

00:52:00.700 --> 00:52:04.230
of the fundamental goals.

00:52:04.230 --> 00:52:04.615
Yes?

00:52:04.615 --> 00:52:06.157
AUDIENCE: Once you give them two
matrices that has the same

00:52:06.157 --> 00:52:09.660
eigenvalues you can ask them
to see if they are

00:52:09.660 --> 00:52:11.560
related in some ways.

00:52:20.648 --> 00:52:23.630
PROFESSOR: Right, so for
example, let's do this one.

00:52:23.630 --> 00:52:39.870
So how are those two
matrices related?

00:52:39.870 --> 00:52:42.700
So they both have eigenvalues
i and minus i.

00:52:42.700 --> 00:52:46.190
This one obviously does because
those are the diagonal

00:52:46.190 --> 00:52:47.720
values and there's
nothing else.

00:52:47.720 --> 00:52:51.290
And this one, you have to do
it by the magic procedure.

00:52:51.290 --> 00:52:52.190
You don't have to.

00:52:52.190 --> 00:52:55.160
And so how are they related?

00:52:55.160 --> 00:53:01.820
So that is some kind of
analysis question.

00:53:01.820 --> 00:53:03.860
And it's quite a difficult
analysis question.

00:53:03.860 --> 00:53:06.560
It tests for really, do they
understand what matrices mean?

00:53:06.560 --> 00:53:09.290
So that's why I've underlined
this word.

00:53:09.290 --> 00:53:14.220
The questions all in this column
are all somehow testing

00:53:14.220 --> 00:53:16.570
that they understand
what things mean.

00:53:16.570 --> 00:53:20.250
So that ties back to the point
I made earlier, which is that

00:53:20.250 --> 00:53:23.780
the whole fundamental point of
asking good questions is to

00:53:23.780 --> 00:53:25.830
avoid rote learning.

00:53:25.830 --> 00:53:27.950
Is that by asking good
questions you're

00:53:27.950 --> 00:53:29.000
fighting rote learning.

00:53:29.000 --> 00:53:32.970
And rote learning is the
bane of most education.

00:53:32.970 --> 00:53:33.210
Right?

00:53:33.210 --> 00:53:38.970
Rote learning is too often
the result of education.

00:53:38.970 --> 00:53:40.570
And it's the-- in my view--

00:53:40.570 --> 00:53:42.500
fundamental problem
with education.

00:53:42.500 --> 00:53:45.190
So by asking questions that are
different you're actually

00:53:45.190 --> 00:53:47.180
starting to fight that
and break the habit.

00:53:47.180 --> 00:53:49.380
So for example, how does
rote learning show up?

00:53:49.380 --> 00:53:56.800
Well, in the bouncing-ball
question, so the force is-- in

00:53:56.800 --> 00:53:57.510
the instant that it's

00:53:57.510 --> 00:53:59.390
stationary, while it's bouncing--

00:53:59.390 --> 00:54:00.640
people say mg.

00:54:05.337 --> 00:54:06.810
While this mg is right.

00:54:06.810 --> 00:54:09.830
The gravity, but the contact--

00:54:09.830 --> 00:54:11.830
let's say the constraint
force--

00:54:11.830 --> 00:54:15.030
in this case it is a very
full-contact force is mg.

00:54:15.030 --> 00:54:19.940
One of the reasons they say that
is the misconception that

00:54:19.940 --> 00:54:23.220
they think a equals 0
because v equals 0.

00:54:23.220 --> 00:54:25.620
So that's one reason.

00:54:25.620 --> 00:54:28.010
But the other reason is that
they've done so many problems

00:54:28.010 --> 00:54:33.020
with books resting on tables,
balls resting on tables, where

00:54:33.020 --> 00:54:34.810
the force is mg.

00:54:34.810 --> 00:54:35.010
Right?

00:54:35.010 --> 00:54:38.090
So they've now induced a new
rule of physics, let's call it

00:54:38.090 --> 00:54:40.390
Newton's fourth law.

00:54:40.390 --> 00:54:46.020
That anytime you see a contact
force it is mg.

00:54:46.020 --> 00:54:51.690
So contact force equals mg maybe
times cosine of theta.

00:54:51.690 --> 00:54:52.610
[LAUGHTER]

00:54:52.610 --> 00:54:53.340
PROFESSOR: Right?

00:54:53.340 --> 00:54:54.080
or sine theta.

00:54:54.080 --> 00:54:57.480
I guess it's mg--

00:54:57.480 --> 00:54:58.820
well, it depends how
you measure theta.

00:54:58.820 --> 00:55:00.500
But theta is the tilt
of the plane.

00:55:00.500 --> 00:55:03.440
So if the plane is tilted 0
degrees just to ground, well

00:55:03.440 --> 00:55:06.050
it's then mg.

00:55:06.050 --> 00:55:10.140
So that kind of learning is the
result of rote learning

00:55:10.140 --> 00:55:12.660
because they've solved problems
without understanding

00:55:12.660 --> 00:55:13.650
what they mean.

00:55:13.650 --> 00:55:16.520
So instead of figuring out that
oh, actually, you could

00:55:16.520 --> 00:55:18.990
understand it from Newton's
Second Law and understanding

00:55:18.990 --> 00:55:22.400
acceleration, they think oh,
there's a new pattern here.

00:55:22.400 --> 00:55:22.700
Right?

00:55:22.700 --> 00:55:25.630
Oh, a new pattern is whenever
I see contact forces it's mg

00:55:25.630 --> 00:55:27.520
times maybe cos theta
or sine theta.

00:55:27.520 --> 00:55:27.850
Yes?

00:55:27.850 --> 00:55:29.760
AUDIENCE: What's the exact
question with that system and

00:55:29.760 --> 00:55:31.850
what's the normal [INAUDIBLE]?

00:55:31.850 --> 00:55:35.490
PROFESSOR: Yeah, so the question
was so you drop the

00:55:35.490 --> 00:55:36.730
ball, say from here.

00:55:36.730 --> 00:55:38.870
And when it bounces off the
steel table there's one

00:55:38.870 --> 00:55:41.480
instant when it's stationary
on steel table.

00:55:41.480 --> 00:55:45.276
And what are the forces
on it at that instant?

00:55:45.276 --> 00:55:47.530
AUDIENCE: I remember
from last week.

00:55:47.530 --> 00:55:48.780
PROFESSOR: Yeah, no,
fair enough.

00:55:48.780 --> 00:55:50.590
I should have stated the
question out again.

00:55:50.590 --> 00:55:54.569
So this is stationary
for an instant.

00:56:03.670 --> 00:56:08.650
All right, so actually the ball
is quite compressed here.

00:56:08.650 --> 00:56:09.138
Yes?

00:56:09.138 --> 00:56:12.879
AUDIENCE: Isn't it impossible
to give an exact answer for

00:56:12.879 --> 00:56:16.458
the force with the [INAUDIBLE]

00:56:16.458 --> 00:56:19.890
if you don't have
the duration?

00:56:19.890 --> 00:56:21.990
PROFESSOR: It is, right.

00:56:21.990 --> 00:56:24.900
So it is impossible to give
the exact answer.

00:56:24.900 --> 00:56:28.340
But what you ask them is, well,
how big is it roughly?

00:56:28.340 --> 00:56:30.750
So I always protect myself
by saying roughly.

00:56:30.750 --> 00:56:33.220
And then you can ask
anything you want.

00:56:33.220 --> 00:56:38.020
And because, really, all I'm
interested in is do they think

00:56:38.020 --> 00:56:40.590
it's 1 times mg or do
they realize it's 10

00:56:40.590 --> 00:56:42.020
to the 4 times mg?

00:56:42.020 --> 00:56:45.410
And those are so far apart
that I don't care about

00:56:45.410 --> 00:56:48.230
factors of two or three
or even 10.

00:56:48.230 --> 00:56:51.140
Now, how can you know that it's
10 to the 4 times mg?

00:56:51.140 --> 00:56:54.070
Well, that is quite
a hard question.

00:56:54.070 --> 00:56:55.790
That's way down there.

00:56:55.790 --> 00:56:59.880
Even though you'll see some
lists of Bloom's Taxonomy say

00:56:59.880 --> 00:57:04.120
estimate is a low-level
skill, not that

00:57:04.120 --> 00:57:05.190
high in Bloom's Taxonomy.

00:57:05.190 --> 00:57:07.570
It's almost like computing
somewhere in comprehension.

00:57:07.570 --> 00:57:08.830
I don't agree with that.

00:57:08.830 --> 00:57:12.430
Because as you saw from the
example where students

00:57:12.430 --> 00:57:16.240
couldn't estimate 3.04 times
5.3, they're terrible at

00:57:16.240 --> 00:57:17.680
estimation.

00:57:17.680 --> 00:57:21.660
So estimation actually hits one
of the big misconceptions

00:57:21.660 --> 00:57:24.240
and reveals a lot of
the misconceptions.

00:57:24.240 --> 00:57:28.190
So I put estimation almost at
the level of synthesis because

00:57:28.190 --> 00:57:30.740
it forces you to really
synthesize your understanding.

00:57:30.740 --> 00:57:32.070
You can't hide behind
formulas.

00:57:32.070 --> 00:57:35.860
So the next thing I'll do is
say, OK, let's estimate this

00:57:35.860 --> 00:57:36.990
and see if you can do that.

00:57:36.990 --> 00:57:38.670
And if they really understand
the system they

00:57:38.670 --> 00:57:39.390
can estimate it.

00:57:39.390 --> 00:57:40.280
But it's quite hard.

00:57:40.280 --> 00:57:42.710
And I find almost no students
can do it on their own.

00:57:42.710 --> 00:57:46.060
But the method of estimation is,
as you say, you do need to

00:57:46.060 --> 00:57:49.490
know the contact time.

00:57:49.490 --> 00:57:55.930
So the acceleration is
not 0 as you say.

00:57:55.930 --> 00:58:00.340
But it's delta v over delta
t, where delta t

00:58:00.340 --> 00:58:03.050
is the contact time.

00:58:03.050 --> 00:58:05.475
Well, it's going v and then it's
pretty much going v up,

00:58:05.475 --> 00:58:07.340
so that's about 2v.

00:58:07.340 --> 00:58:09.080
But I don't care about
factors of 2.

00:58:11.680 --> 00:58:13.150
And then, what's the
contact time?

00:58:13.150 --> 00:58:16.860
Well, there's a couple methods
for doing the contact time.

00:58:16.860 --> 00:58:20.030
One is you listen
for the pitch.

00:58:20.030 --> 00:58:23.480
And whatever the highest
frequency in the pitch is--

00:58:23.480 --> 00:58:26.540
suppose it's 10 to
the 4 hertz--

00:58:26.540 --> 00:58:29.420
well, then 1 over that time,
1 over the frequency

00:58:29.420 --> 00:58:30.730
is roughly a time.

00:58:30.730 --> 00:58:33.170
So it's probably the
contact time.

00:58:33.170 --> 00:58:34.520
So that's one approach.

00:58:34.520 --> 00:58:36.860
The other approach is to say
well, actually, physically

00:58:36.860 --> 00:58:39.170
what's happening?

00:58:39.170 --> 00:58:42.260
The ball is hitting
the bottom.

00:58:42.260 --> 00:58:45.260
And this end compressing.

00:58:45.260 --> 00:58:46.310
But this end keeps going.

00:58:46.310 --> 00:58:49.690
Because it has no knowledge that
the bottom of the ball

00:58:49.690 --> 00:58:50.740
hit the ground.

00:58:50.740 --> 00:58:52.290
How's it going to
know about that?

00:58:52.290 --> 00:58:54.110
Well, the bottom of the
ball has to tell it.

00:58:54.110 --> 00:58:55.130
How's it going to tell it?

00:58:55.130 --> 00:58:56.210
Well, it has to send some
kind of signal.

00:58:56.210 --> 00:58:57.270
How does it send signal?

00:58:57.270 --> 00:58:58.130
Sound.

00:58:58.130 --> 00:59:06.170
So it sends a sound
wave upward.

00:59:06.170 --> 00:59:09.980
And the sound wave travels in
steel about 5 or 10 kilometers

00:59:09.980 --> 00:59:11.070
per second.

00:59:11.070 --> 00:59:14.270
So you suppose it's a
5-centimeter ball, then it's

00:59:14.270 --> 00:59:17.260
about 10 to the minus 5 seconds
is your contact time.

00:59:17.260 --> 00:59:18.510
So this is really short.

00:59:23.930 --> 00:59:28.640
So suppose v is something like a
meter per second, and divide

00:59:28.640 --> 00:59:30.440
it by 10 to the 5 seconds.

00:59:30.440 --> 00:59:32.700
You're talking about something
like 10 to the 5 meters per

00:59:32.700 --> 00:59:37.915
second squared, which is 10 to
the 4 times the acceleration

00:59:37.915 --> 00:59:40.040
due to gravity.

00:59:40.040 --> 00:59:40.430
OK?

00:59:40.430 --> 00:59:45.960
So I went through because I
think it's interesting but

00:59:45.960 --> 00:59:49.160
also to show that estimating
actually requires generally,

00:59:49.160 --> 00:59:50.180
very high-level skills.

00:59:50.180 --> 00:59:52.090
And it's quite hard
for the students.

00:59:52.090 --> 00:59:53.540
Therefore you should do it.

00:59:53.540 --> 00:59:55.530
So there are some people who
say, well, it's very hard for

00:59:55.530 --> 00:59:56.000
the students.

00:59:56.000 --> 00:59:57.420
Don't do it.

00:59:57.420 --> 00:59:59.690
But again, there's another rule
of thumb in teaching,

00:59:59.690 --> 01:00:02.330
which is nobody ever learned
anything that you didn't

01:00:02.330 --> 01:00:03.465
actually try to help
them with.

01:00:03.465 --> 01:00:04.440
Well, that's not quite true.

01:00:04.440 --> 01:00:06.490
But if you never teach something
they're not very

01:00:06.490 --> 01:00:07.400
likely to learn it.

01:00:07.400 --> 01:00:09.900
So if it's something hard but
valuable you have to start

01:00:09.900 --> 01:00:14.520
teaching at some point,
which is why I put

01:00:14.520 --> 01:00:15.585
up that graph earlier.

01:00:15.585 --> 01:00:16.790
Oh, it's gone now.

01:00:16.790 --> 01:00:20.120
Where in the earlier stages of
teaching you do things more

01:00:20.120 --> 01:00:21.050
approximately.

01:00:21.050 --> 01:00:25.340
And then in the later stages
you do it more exactly.

01:00:25.340 --> 01:00:28.380
So what I've told you
now is a slight lie.

01:00:28.380 --> 01:00:29.960
So this brings up the
question from last

01:00:29.960 --> 01:00:31.960
time, what about lying?

01:00:31.960 --> 01:00:32.530
Is it useful?

01:00:32.530 --> 01:00:36.210
Yes, it's essential because this
argument is simple enough

01:00:36.210 --> 01:00:37.430
that once you understand
it you can just

01:00:37.430 --> 01:00:38.870
keep it in your head.

01:00:38.870 --> 01:00:43.150
And it's a bit of a lie, the
reason being that the ball

01:00:43.150 --> 01:00:45.360
doesn't have a uniform
cross section.

01:00:45.360 --> 01:00:49.130
So as the ball compresses the
contact area changes, whereas

01:00:49.130 --> 01:00:52.900
if the ball were cube or a rod
the contact area would stay

01:00:52.900 --> 01:00:54.140
the same as it compressed.

01:00:54.140 --> 01:00:57.210
So there's a correction
factor because the

01:00:57.210 --> 01:00:58.840
contact area changes.

01:00:58.840 --> 01:01:01.700
Now, that correction factor
is not very big.

01:01:01.700 --> 01:01:03.920
It turns out to be the
fifth root of some

01:01:03.920 --> 01:01:05.420
dimensionless thing.

01:01:05.420 --> 01:01:09.640
And so this sound-wave argument
you put in to the 4/5

01:01:09.640 --> 01:01:12.070
power and then you put in the
other thing to the 1/5 power.

01:01:12.070 --> 01:01:14.970
So it's almost correct for
this spherical ball.

01:01:14.970 --> 01:01:17.560
So in a later of course
it actually

01:01:17.560 --> 01:01:19.360
adjusts for that factor.

01:01:19.360 --> 01:01:21.370
And then in a much later course,
probably, what I would

01:01:21.370 --> 01:01:26.040
do is calculate the exact 2 pi
over whatever factor that

01:01:26.040 --> 01:01:31.600
shows up as well, by way of
increasing the symbolic

01:01:31.600 --> 01:01:32.730
complexity.

01:01:32.730 --> 01:01:37.760
But even this estimate, doing
that is conceptually hard.

01:01:37.760 --> 01:01:41.040
So I would say start
that early.

01:01:41.040 --> 01:01:42.520
AUDIENCE: I think the point
I was trying to

01:01:42.520 --> 01:01:45.260
make was that this--

01:01:45.260 --> 01:01:49.350
I suspect that the students
answered that wrong because of

01:01:49.350 --> 01:01:52.682
real problem solving, and that
they expect there to be a

01:01:52.682 --> 01:01:57.080
solution given the data
that you [INAUDIBLE].

01:01:57.080 --> 01:02:00.160
PROFESSOR: Well, if you've
worked with them a bit on

01:02:00.160 --> 01:02:02.280
estimating they know that
they're going to have to do

01:02:02.280 --> 01:02:02.970
some thinking.

01:02:02.970 --> 01:02:07.530
If you say compute the force
I agree with you for sure.

01:02:07.530 --> 01:02:09.760
They're going to think they have
to be able to do it from

01:02:09.760 --> 01:02:10.410
the data there.

01:02:10.410 --> 01:02:12.555
And they'll just say it's got
to be mg because that's the

01:02:12.555 --> 01:02:13.420
only other force I know.

01:02:13.420 --> 01:02:17.550
But if you say estimate then
there is a bit of a queue that

01:02:17.550 --> 01:02:20.080
they have to include some other
information which might

01:02:20.080 --> 01:02:21.350
not put in the problem.

01:02:21.350 --> 01:02:22.820
And so that mitigates
the rote learning.

01:02:22.820 --> 01:02:25.670
But what I find, even then, is
they usually still can't do it

01:02:25.670 --> 01:02:29.270
because their misconceptions
about acceleration are so deep

01:02:29.270 --> 01:02:30.750
and about equilibrium
and force.

01:02:30.750 --> 01:02:32.255
They think f equals
mv, basically.

01:02:36.980 --> 01:02:43.630
OK, so let's just look at
what we've done here.

01:02:43.630 --> 01:02:46.970
So I would say you can
define lambda.

01:02:46.970 --> 01:02:49.260
You can define eigenvector.

01:02:49.260 --> 01:02:52.970
You can even say state the
computational procedure.

01:02:52.970 --> 01:02:56.640
I'm not sure where
I would put that.

01:02:56.640 --> 01:03:00.360
Depending on how people learn
it, this could be purely a

01:03:00.360 --> 01:03:01.610
knowledge question.

01:03:09.120 --> 01:03:10.960
Because people could state the
procedure but not really

01:03:10.960 --> 01:03:12.930
understand it, not be
able to do anything.

01:03:12.930 --> 01:03:16.410
Or actually, you could say
program the procedure.

01:03:16.410 --> 01:03:18.530
Well, that would be something
over here probably.

01:03:18.530 --> 01:03:20.400
Because to program it you
probably have to understand

01:03:20.400 --> 01:03:22.130
what you're doing pretty well.

01:03:22.130 --> 01:03:25.480
So stating the procedure, it
depends how you ask them to

01:03:25.480 --> 01:03:27.250
state it, whether it's
a low-level or

01:03:27.250 --> 01:03:28.140
a high-level question.

01:03:28.140 --> 01:03:30.806
So I'll put program over here.

01:03:47.570 --> 01:03:51.120
OK, so we've gone down and up.

01:03:51.120 --> 01:03:54.340
And again, I want to remind you,
I'm not saying all your

01:03:54.340 --> 01:03:55.940
questions need to be here.

01:03:55.940 --> 01:04:01.380
But generally, the questions are
too much over here and not

01:04:01.380 --> 01:04:02.470
enough over here.

01:04:02.470 --> 01:04:05.530
So this gives you a recipe for
thinking of new questions.

01:04:05.530 --> 01:04:05.820
Yes?

01:04:05.820 --> 01:04:08.774
AUDIENCE: So throughout the
course do you basically, maybe

01:04:08.774 --> 01:04:12.260
start on the first three in
the beginning and then you

01:04:12.260 --> 01:04:15.248
move it more through until you
reach the end of the course?

01:04:15.248 --> 01:04:17.670
PROFESSOR: More fractal.

01:04:17.670 --> 01:04:21.030
The question was as the course
moves on do you move more

01:04:21.030 --> 01:04:22.340
towards synthesis?

01:04:22.340 --> 01:04:24.230
I actually try to
make it fractal.

01:04:24.230 --> 01:04:29.330
So within each unit and each day
even, I try to maybe have

01:04:29.330 --> 01:04:31.850
something, knowledge or
comprehension just to make

01:04:31.850 --> 01:04:33.270
sure everyone's tracking.

01:04:33.270 --> 01:04:36.910
But try to have something
interesting as

01:04:36.910 --> 01:04:37.860
well, all the time.

01:04:37.860 --> 01:04:41.690
So something synthesis,
analysis, maybe some evaluate.

01:04:41.690 --> 01:04:43.920
And so each problem set--
for example--

01:04:43.920 --> 01:04:46.530
I'll put, generally,
warm-up questions.

01:04:46.530 --> 01:04:50.460
So basically they're marked warm
up so that people know

01:04:50.460 --> 01:04:53.000
OK, those are going to be
knowledge and comprehension.

01:04:53.000 --> 01:04:53.940
And you need that.

01:04:53.940 --> 01:04:56.290
Because otherwise there's no
point trying to do synthesis

01:04:56.290 --> 01:04:58.060
if you don't have the
base knowledge.

01:04:58.060 --> 01:04:59.930
But just make sure you
understand those,

01:04:59.930 --> 01:05:01.310
just in your sleep.

01:05:01.310 --> 01:05:04.210
And then regular problems, which
tend to be somewhere in

01:05:04.210 --> 01:05:07.750
the middle, say application
or analysis.

01:05:07.750 --> 01:05:09.890
And then bonus problems which
are just optional.

01:05:09.890 --> 01:05:12.210
But they're for people who
either find all the other

01:05:12.210 --> 01:05:14.750
problems easy or are
really curious.

01:05:14.750 --> 01:05:17.970
For them I put either synthesis
or evaluation.

01:05:17.970 --> 01:05:25.200
For example, in the
approximation class the last

01:05:25.200 --> 01:05:29.320
problem set had design an
email indexing system.

01:05:29.320 --> 01:05:31.420
So that was the bonus problem.

01:05:31.420 --> 01:05:34.630
And there was a bunch of warm-up
and regular problems

01:05:34.630 --> 01:05:37.240
which were involving Unix
text processing.

01:05:37.240 --> 01:05:39.170
And then for the people who are
really curious actually,

01:05:39.170 --> 01:05:42.780
put it all together and make a
really fast email-indexing

01:05:42.780 --> 01:05:45.020
system so you can just find any
email that you want just

01:05:45.020 --> 01:05:46.350
by doing keyword search.

01:05:46.350 --> 01:05:51.180
Sort of like a web search but
just on your email inbox.

01:05:51.180 --> 01:05:53.210
Because I actually
use that myself.

01:05:53.210 --> 01:05:55.980
Because I find folders
are just hopeless.

01:05:55.980 --> 01:05:57.150
It just takes all my time.

01:05:57.150 --> 01:05:58.910
I have to figure out what
folder things are in.

01:05:58.910 --> 01:06:00.210
And that could be many.

01:06:00.210 --> 01:06:03.060
So I just keep it all in one
giant inbox with, I think,

01:06:03.060 --> 01:06:05.570
150,000 messages in it.

01:06:05.570 --> 01:06:06.880
And I just search
through that.

01:06:06.880 --> 01:06:09.680
And I have an index that's
rebuilt every week or so.

01:06:09.680 --> 01:06:11.870
And so I can search through
it really fast.

01:06:11.870 --> 01:06:15.360
So it's actually very practical
problem and it gives

01:06:15.360 --> 01:06:17.290
you an example of the levels
of things you can ask.

01:06:17.290 --> 01:06:19.520
So try to do it on
a fractal scale.

01:06:19.520 --> 01:06:23.490
Each class should have
something, mix the levels each

01:06:23.490 --> 01:06:26.090
homework, the exam.

01:06:26.090 --> 01:06:29.886
So the general rule is to
mix them up all the way.

01:06:29.886 --> 01:06:30.820
OK?

01:06:30.820 --> 01:06:37.200
So hopefully, from that, you
feel confident that you have

01:06:37.200 --> 01:06:41.250
tools that you can make
interesting questions.

01:06:41.250 --> 01:06:44.830
And this does have lots of
payoffs, which one of them is

01:06:44.830 --> 01:06:48.520
that questions that are
enjoyable and educational,

01:06:48.520 --> 01:06:49.940
students love them.

01:06:49.940 --> 01:06:54.870
So when I practiced what I
preached and made these kind

01:06:54.870 --> 01:06:59.320
of problems, mix of problems for
my classes, often students

01:06:59.320 --> 01:07:04.450
have said, oh, can you please
have more problems?

01:07:04.450 --> 01:07:06.710
Which is very rare.

01:07:06.710 --> 01:07:08.450
They said, oh, these are some
of the most interesting

01:07:08.450 --> 01:07:10.140
problems I'm likely
to get at MIT.

01:07:10.140 --> 01:07:13.570
And I used to read them
out in my living of my

01:07:13.570 --> 01:07:15.820
independent-living group just
so that other people could

01:07:15.820 --> 01:07:17.170
hear the interesting problems
and we'd try

01:07:17.170 --> 01:07:18.680
to solve them together.

01:07:18.680 --> 01:07:21.860
And then I've had several emails
after class finished,

01:07:21.860 --> 01:07:24.270
saying, oh, you promised to post
the optional problem set.

01:07:24.270 --> 01:07:26.080
Where is it?

01:07:26.080 --> 01:07:29.840
So it's because the problems,
actually, somehow connect to

01:07:29.840 --> 01:07:32.710
things that people find
real and interesting.

01:07:32.710 --> 01:07:35.870
So that's a mix of
the perceptual.

01:07:35.870 --> 01:07:38.180
Don't make it just purely
symbol manipulation.

01:07:38.180 --> 01:07:40.540
Try to connect to ways people
look at the world.

01:07:40.540 --> 01:07:44.994
But also, try to connect to
higher-level reasoning skills.

01:07:44.994 --> 01:07:45.466
Question?

01:07:45.466 --> 01:07:47.354
AUDIENCE: Do you always
use bonus problems?

01:07:47.354 --> 01:07:48.330
PROFESSOR: I do.

01:07:48.330 --> 01:07:49.570
I find that works really well.

01:07:49.570 --> 01:07:52.955
Because it's like a
pressure-escape valve.

01:07:55.950 --> 01:07:59.740
It caters for the diversity of
backgrounds in the class.

01:07:59.740 --> 01:08:03.980
The people who are feeling very
worried by the material,

01:08:03.980 --> 01:08:06.680
they can just skip
them, no problem.

01:08:06.680 --> 01:08:08.480
And they don't feel like
they have to do them.

01:08:08.480 --> 01:08:10.600
And they don't feel like, oh
my god, I can't do them.

01:08:10.600 --> 01:08:12.640
I'm going to get points off.

01:08:12.640 --> 01:08:15.030
And the people who find the
other stuff easy, they find

01:08:15.030 --> 01:08:16.080
something for them too.

01:08:16.080 --> 01:08:20.450
So yeah, I try to always
use bonus problems.

01:08:20.450 --> 01:08:26.330
And I learned that from Knuth's
book, called Concrete

01:08:26.330 --> 01:08:27.800
Mathematics.

01:08:27.800 --> 01:08:30.279
So actually, I think they have
five levels of problems at the

01:08:30.279 --> 01:08:31.050
end of every chapter.

01:08:31.050 --> 01:08:32.460
There's warm ups.

01:08:32.460 --> 01:08:34.850
There's homework problems.

01:08:34.850 --> 01:08:38.590
There's exam problems,
bonus problems,

01:08:38.590 --> 01:08:39.630
and research problems.

01:08:39.630 --> 01:08:41.029
So the research problems
were the ones

01:08:41.029 --> 01:08:43.370
that are not yet solved.

01:08:43.370 --> 01:08:44.680
So at least you know they're
not yet solved.

01:08:44.680 --> 01:08:47.910
So you're going to be spending
a while on them.

01:08:47.910 --> 01:08:49.850
And then in the second edition
I think some of them were

01:08:49.850 --> 01:08:52.500
actually solved.

