01:11:44.420 --> 01:11:47.710
But even I find the
15% very useful.

01:11:47.710 --> 01:11:50.080
And I found that--

01:11:50.080 --> 01:11:52.970
people even in the past, when
the response rate was 30% in

01:11:52.970 --> 01:11:54.960
another class people said,
I didn't have a

01:11:54.960 --> 01:11:56.050
question all the time.

01:11:56.050 --> 01:11:58.450
But I knew when I did
I could ask it.

01:11:58.450 --> 01:12:00.420
So even the 15% isn't bad.

01:12:00.420 --> 01:12:01.670
It's still useful.

01:12:01.670 --> 01:12:03.090
But yeah, I would like
it to be higher.

01:12:03.090 --> 01:12:06.108
And I'll tell you
how that goes.

01:12:06.108 --> 01:12:06.570
Question?

01:12:06.570 --> 01:12:08.880
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]?

01:12:08.880 --> 01:12:09.804
Wiggins and--

01:12:09.804 --> 01:12:10.900
PROFESSOR: McTighe, yeah.

01:12:10.900 --> 01:12:13.640
AUDIENCE: Oh, McTighe.

01:12:13.640 --> 01:12:14.960
Where are they based?

01:12:14.960 --> 01:12:17.010
PROFESSOR: So where are they?

01:12:17.010 --> 01:12:18.730
They're in New Jersey, and
they actually consult on

01:12:18.730 --> 01:12:23.230
educational course design and
run workshops and courses.

01:12:23.230 --> 01:12:24.770
And we actually invited
Wiggins last

01:12:24.770 --> 01:12:25.770
year to come and speak.

01:12:25.770 --> 01:12:29.000
So I'll put a short reading
selection from their book

01:12:29.000 --> 01:12:33.870
called Understanding By Design
for optional reading for

01:12:33.870 --> 01:12:37.060
people so then you can learn
more about that.

01:12:37.060 --> 01:12:40.600
I find the basic form that
they say very useful.

01:12:40.600 --> 01:12:44.300
I find applying it the way they
describe, sometimes I

01:12:44.300 --> 01:12:45.750
just can't square it.

01:12:45.750 --> 01:12:48.990
But it may resonate with
you quite well.

01:12:48.990 --> 01:12:50.820
And the overall approach
resonates very

01:12:50.820 --> 01:12:51.570
strongly with me.

01:12:51.570 --> 01:12:53.410
So hopefully you will
like it too.

01:12:53.410 --> 01:12:56.820
So I'll put that on the website
and some readings for

01:12:56.820 --> 01:13:00.284
next time about course design.

01:13:00.284 --> 01:13:00.780
Yes?

01:13:00.780 --> 01:13:02.880
AUDIENCE: Just a comment,
actually on your web page,

01:13:02.880 --> 01:13:05.620
where the response
sheet [INAUDIBLE]

01:13:05.620 --> 01:13:09.644
and situation where only a few
people were very dislike the

01:13:09.644 --> 01:13:10.894
current [INAUDIBLE].

01:13:13.198 --> 01:13:16.010
They don't like it this way and
so they want to change it.

01:13:16.010 --> 01:13:18.714
But the 80% who don't
feel [INAUDIBLE] is

01:13:18.714 --> 01:13:20.090
actually OK with it.

01:13:20.090 --> 01:13:20.640
[INAUDIBLE] the change.

01:13:20.640 --> 01:13:22.730
It makes most people unhappy.

01:13:22.730 --> 01:13:25.180
PROFESSOR: Unhappy, right,
so that can happen.

01:13:25.180 --> 01:13:28.480
And so that's the silent
majority problem.

01:13:28.480 --> 01:13:30.540
So what I do when I get comments
like people saying,

01:13:30.540 --> 01:13:32.500
well, I wasn't happy
about this.

01:13:32.500 --> 01:13:34.220
Sometimes what I do is--

01:13:34.220 --> 01:13:35.780
especially if it doesn't
resonate with my intuition

01:13:35.780 --> 01:13:37.470
about how things were
going, and I thought

01:13:37.470 --> 01:13:38.400
they were going well--

01:13:38.400 --> 01:13:41.950
I'll say, well, there were a few
comments about this issue.

01:13:41.950 --> 01:13:43.700
What do people think?

01:13:43.700 --> 01:13:46.040
And just take an informal
straw pole

01:13:46.040 --> 01:13:47.636
before I make big changes.

01:13:47.636 --> 01:13:49.872
AUDIENCE: I think it helps to
have a positive question on

01:13:49.872 --> 01:13:52.348
[INAUDIBLE], like,
what did you take

01:13:52.348 --> 01:13:53.324
away from this lecture?

01:13:53.324 --> 01:13:54.300
Or what did you really
understand?

01:13:54.300 --> 01:13:55.630
PROFESSOR: Right, I think
that's right.

01:13:55.630 --> 01:13:57.050
It helps to have a positive
question.

01:13:57.050 --> 01:14:01.110
So that's why I say, either what
you take away, or what

01:14:01.110 --> 01:14:01.980
helped or hurt?

01:14:01.980 --> 01:14:05.830
So there's an opportunity to
say something helpful.

01:14:05.830 --> 01:14:10.390
And any other comments is also
interpreted in a positive way.

01:14:10.390 --> 01:14:12.780
Answers from Lecture
5 to questions

01:14:12.780 --> 01:14:14.340
generated in Lecture 4.

01:14:16.944 --> 01:14:19.760
PROFESSOR: OK, and questions
from last time.

01:14:19.760 --> 01:14:23.340
So they grouped into
several ones.

01:14:23.340 --> 01:14:29.300
One is how should you choose
your levels of your problems--

01:14:29.300 --> 01:14:31.200
say, in class or in homeworks--
among the

01:14:31.200 --> 01:14:34.470
different levels of
Bloom's Taxonomy?

01:14:34.470 --> 01:14:38.620
Should it be, for example all
towards the evaluation?

01:14:38.620 --> 01:14:41.340
So your side would be here,
sort of the high level.

01:14:41.340 --> 01:14:42.370
A Mix?

01:14:42.370 --> 01:14:43.090
A flat mix?

01:14:43.090 --> 01:14:45.770
Should it be peaked towards the
middle with some tails?

01:14:45.770 --> 01:14:49.700
So that depends, partly,
on your course design.

01:14:49.700 --> 01:14:52.110
So to answer that question, you
can't really answer that

01:14:52.110 --> 01:14:55.360
question until you figure out
what your course goals are.

01:14:55.360 --> 01:14:58.800
So in some ways there's an
argument for doing course

01:14:58.800 --> 01:15:03.320
design first and then working on
what problems to do and how

01:15:03.320 --> 01:15:04.470
to design problems.

01:15:04.470 --> 01:15:06.410
But actually, I like the
other way around.

01:15:06.410 --> 01:15:08.400
I like doing course
design second.

01:15:08.400 --> 01:15:11.020
Because actually, doing problems
is concrete enough to

01:15:11.020 --> 01:15:11.800
do something.

01:15:11.800 --> 01:15:16.130
And then it leads to questions
about course design, which

01:15:16.130 --> 01:15:19.650
we'll answer how to
mix the levels.

01:15:19.650 --> 01:15:25.380
OK, another one was several
people wanted to know, why is

01:15:25.380 --> 01:15:27.640
tension not a force?

01:15:27.640 --> 01:15:29.130
Or in fact, maybe is a force.

01:15:29.130 --> 01:15:30.390
So let me explain that.

01:15:30.390 --> 01:15:33.680
Because that actually gives you
another example of sorting

01:15:33.680 --> 01:15:34.700
out misconceptions.

01:15:34.700 --> 01:15:35.690
So it's always useful.

01:15:35.690 --> 01:15:38.820
So I'll show you the sequence
of questions I used with

01:15:38.820 --> 01:15:41.910
myself when I finally
convinced that

01:15:41.910 --> 01:15:43.360
tension wasn't a force.

01:15:43.360 --> 01:15:46.230
And here's how I did it.

01:15:46.230 --> 01:15:49.230
And then I used the same
sequence of questions with

01:15:49.230 --> 01:15:51.550
students to fight the
misconception that's been

01:15:51.550 --> 01:15:54.260
induced by many pictures of--

01:15:54.260 --> 01:15:55.920
for example-- a pulley.

01:15:55.920 --> 01:16:00.170
And here's a rope and
there's tension.

01:16:00.170 --> 01:16:01.440
Sorry, this is actually
done the other way.

01:16:01.440 --> 01:16:02.690
So here's the rope.

01:16:05.140 --> 01:16:07.010
And there's a t labeled there.

01:16:07.010 --> 01:16:11.430
And then on the mass there's a
force labeled as t upward.

01:16:11.430 --> 01:16:13.565
So when you see that you think,
oh, tension's a force.

01:16:13.565 --> 01:16:15.250
So you see that a whole bunch
of times and you're pretty

01:16:15.250 --> 01:16:16.460
sure of it.

01:16:16.460 --> 01:16:21.060
So the sequence of questions
is as follows--

01:16:21.060 --> 01:16:27.210
say OK, here's a tree.

01:16:31.800 --> 01:16:37.840
And I'm going to tie a rope to
the tree, rope or a string,

01:16:37.840 --> 01:16:39.590
it's a mass-less thing.

01:16:39.590 --> 01:16:40.900
And I put a force on it.

01:16:45.880 --> 01:16:48.130
OK, so I'm going to
pull that tree.

01:16:48.130 --> 01:16:49.250
The tree's not going
to go anywhere.

01:16:49.250 --> 01:16:50.500
We're going to pull
on the rope with

01:16:50.500 --> 01:16:52.240
100 newtons of force.

01:16:52.240 --> 01:16:55.910
OK, so you can try this
yourself too.

01:16:55.910 --> 01:16:57.350
What's the tension
in the string?

01:17:01.660 --> 01:17:05.880
OK, so take 30 seconds and
I'll take a tension.

01:17:11.220 --> 01:17:12.470
OK, a tension, anyone?

01:17:21.204 --> 01:17:22.945
AUDIENCE: 100 newtons.

01:17:22.945 --> 01:17:27.570
PROFESSOR: OK, so in fact
that is 100 newtons.

01:17:27.570 --> 01:17:29.140
And most people will
say 100 newtons.

01:17:29.140 --> 01:17:32.770
OK, so now the next
question is this--

01:17:32.770 --> 01:17:43.010
here is a river and
here's a rope.

01:17:43.010 --> 01:17:52.660
And me and a friend each pull on
the rope with 100 newtons.

01:17:52.660 --> 01:17:53.910
OK?

01:18:03.800 --> 01:18:07.350
OK, so discuss with
your neighbor--

01:18:07.350 --> 01:18:10.800
a, b, or c, what's the
tension in the rope?

01:18:10.800 --> 01:18:12.050
And we'll take a vote.

01:18:14.770 --> 01:18:19.200
OK, so take 10 seconds,
get your vote ready.

01:18:19.200 --> 01:18:23.440
We'll take a quick straw pole.

01:18:23.440 --> 01:18:24.980
Who votes for 0 newtons?

01:18:30.040 --> 01:18:31.345
Who votes for 100 newtons?

01:18:36.420 --> 01:18:38.210
Who votes for 200 newtons?

01:18:42.190 --> 01:18:48.820
OK, so now here, how do you know
what it's going to be?

01:18:48.820 --> 01:18:50.320
Well, you make a
force diagram.

01:18:50.320 --> 01:18:53.090
And there's a way to convince
yourself that there's no doubt

01:18:53.090 --> 01:18:54.560
about what it should be.

01:18:54.560 --> 01:18:56.630
And we just draw the forces
on the rope here.

01:18:56.630 --> 01:18:58.140
Oh, we've already done that.

01:18:58.140 --> 01:18:59.730
Let's draw the forces on
the rope up there.

01:19:07.640 --> 01:19:09.230
Well, what are the forces
on the rope here?

01:19:09.230 --> 01:19:11.520
Well, it's 100 newtons
from you.

01:19:11.520 --> 01:19:13.620
But there must also be 100
newtons from the tree.

01:19:16.290 --> 01:19:16.740
All right?

01:19:16.740 --> 01:19:20.350
So in fact, these two situations
are identical.

01:19:20.350 --> 01:19:22.415
So yeah, 100 newtons seems
pretty clear here.

01:19:22.415 --> 01:19:24.670
So it has to be 100 newtons
up there too.

01:19:28.590 --> 01:19:30.930
OK, now that--

01:19:30.930 --> 01:19:32.410
so far-- isn't the hard part.

01:19:32.410 --> 01:19:36.320
But now is when you actually
create the contradiction with

01:19:36.320 --> 01:19:37.540
the idea of it being a force.

01:19:37.540 --> 01:19:42.480
It can't be a force because if
it were a force you would just

01:19:42.480 --> 01:19:44.700
add up vectors.

01:19:44.700 --> 01:19:44.940
Right?

01:19:44.940 --> 01:19:47.570
So there's a couple answers
you get if it was a force.

01:19:47.570 --> 01:19:49.960
If you're a bit sloppy you'd
just add up the magnitudes and

01:19:49.960 --> 01:19:51.870
get 200 newtons.

01:19:51.870 --> 01:19:53.460
If it's really a vector--

01:19:53.460 --> 01:19:55.260
you're putting two vectors
on it, two forces--

01:19:55.260 --> 01:19:57.440
you should get 0 because they're
two opposite forces.

01:19:57.440 --> 01:19:59.460
But actually you get 100.

01:19:59.460 --> 01:20:01.630
The only way to get 100 is that
the tension has to be

01:20:01.630 --> 01:20:03.810
something completely different
from a force.

01:20:03.810 --> 01:20:05.610
So that's how you know
it's not a force.

01:20:05.610 --> 01:20:06.880
But how do what it is?

01:20:06.880 --> 01:20:12.170
Well, it turns out
to be a tensor.

01:20:12.170 --> 01:20:13.310
So it's not a vector.

01:20:13.310 --> 01:20:14.320
Forces are vectors.

01:20:14.320 --> 01:20:17.960
It adds differently
than vectors do.

01:20:17.960 --> 01:20:19.730
It adds like a tensor.

01:20:19.730 --> 01:20:23.130
So tension is more
like a pressure.

01:20:23.130 --> 01:20:25.190
It doesn't have a particular
direction.

01:20:25.190 --> 01:20:26.560
Pressure is in all directions.

01:20:26.560 --> 01:20:29.590
So things like that, they can't
be described by vectors.

01:20:29.590 --> 01:20:30.610
So you need something else.

01:20:30.610 --> 01:20:32.520
And that's why we introduced
tensors.

01:20:32.520 --> 01:20:35.010
So now, in freshman physics I
wouldn't give them a whole

01:20:35.010 --> 01:20:36.360
story about tensors.

01:20:36.360 --> 01:20:40.650
But I do actually teach this
much of it so that they know

01:20:40.650 --> 01:20:42.230
that is a different object.

01:20:42.230 --> 01:20:44.880
And then what do I
do about this?

01:20:44.880 --> 01:20:50.840
Well, I won't write t unless
it's for myself.

01:20:50.840 --> 01:20:53.180
But for the students I think
it's sloppy and it increases

01:20:53.180 --> 01:20:54.300
misconception.

01:20:54.300 --> 01:20:58.020
It's much better to write the
force sub t, which is the

01:20:58.020 --> 01:20:59.630
force due to tension.

01:20:59.630 --> 01:21:00.030
OK?

01:21:00.030 --> 01:21:03.170
So even a slight change like
that can mitigate the rote

01:21:03.170 --> 01:21:05.930
learning, where people think
oh, tension's a force.

01:21:05.930 --> 01:21:08.100
Because you always see it drawn
like every other force.

01:21:08.100 --> 01:21:14.077
There's mg down, There's t
up, must be a force too.

01:21:14.077 --> 01:21:15.327
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]?

01:21:22.170 --> 01:21:25.120
PROFESSOR: What are the two
objects you hit it with to

01:21:25.120 --> 01:21:26.370
make a scalar?

01:21:29.890 --> 01:21:31.920
It's the two directions
that you're

01:21:31.920 --> 01:21:33.600
interested in, basically.

01:21:33.600 --> 01:21:39.210
So it would be the x direction
or the direction along the

01:21:39.210 --> 01:21:42.854
string and the direction
along the string.

01:21:42.854 --> 01:21:45.546
AUDIENCE: So it's the
two direction then?

01:21:45.546 --> 01:21:48.700
PROFESSOR: You can use the
same direction twice.

01:21:48.700 --> 01:21:49.840
So it's the direction
along the string

01:21:49.840 --> 01:21:50.560
and along the string.

01:21:50.560 --> 01:21:53.620
There's no cross direction.

01:21:53.620 --> 01:21:54.580
So it has no shear.

01:21:54.580 --> 01:21:56.700
So there's no cross direction.

01:21:56.700 --> 01:21:59.880
So it's some component, tension
is one component of

01:21:59.880 --> 01:22:02.530
the stress tensor.

01:22:02.530 --> 01:22:04.895
So now, again, freshman don't
need to know all the details.

01:22:08.030 --> 01:22:13.980
This is back to the subject of
lying they do need to not be

01:22:13.980 --> 01:22:15.310
told fundamental lies.

01:22:15.310 --> 01:22:20.080
Like for example, tension
is a force.

01:22:20.080 --> 01:22:24.520
OK, so now, how do you deal with
misconceptions that show

01:22:24.520 --> 01:22:25.880
up on problem sets?

01:22:25.880 --> 01:22:26.690
This is a good question.

01:22:26.690 --> 01:22:29.150
So the point was made well, in
class you can sort it out

01:22:29.150 --> 01:22:29.630
right then.

01:22:29.630 --> 01:22:32.030
Suppose you ask a question, say,
about the Ideal Gas Law.

01:22:32.030 --> 01:22:34.760
And you find that people have
confused the Ideal Gas Law and

01:22:34.760 --> 01:22:35.910
the Adiabatic Gas Law.

01:22:35.910 --> 01:22:38.050
Well, you can talk about it
right then, which is a good

01:22:38.050 --> 01:22:39.740
reason to do those
things in class.

01:22:39.740 --> 01:22:41.900
What happens on the problem
set if you find there's a

01:22:41.900 --> 01:22:43.120
bunch of misconceptions?

01:22:43.120 --> 01:22:45.860
Well, one thing is, the first
time you do the problem set,

01:22:45.860 --> 01:22:46.830
yeah it's a bit of a problem.

01:22:46.830 --> 01:22:49.180
Because you don't know what the
misconceptions are unless

01:22:49.180 --> 01:22:51.260
you've researched
ahead of time.

01:22:51.260 --> 01:22:54.660
But the second time you do the
class you know what they are.

01:22:54.660 --> 01:22:56.700
So you can address the
misconceptions in

01:22:56.700 --> 01:22:58.040
the solution set.

01:22:58.040 --> 01:23:01.870
So when I'm not totally sleep
deprived I always try to get

01:23:01.870 --> 01:23:05.110
the solution set out the exact
same day that the problem set

01:23:05.110 --> 01:23:05.880
is turned in.

01:23:05.880 --> 01:23:07.840
So the students can
right away see.

01:23:07.840 --> 01:23:09.920
They can turn in their problem
set, pick up a solution set or

01:23:09.920 --> 01:23:11.330
look at it online.

01:23:11.330 --> 01:23:13.390
So they can right away
get quick feedback.

01:23:13.390 --> 01:23:17.710
And they can sort out the
misconceptions that way.

01:23:17.710 --> 01:23:20.050
So that's a good question.

01:23:20.050 --> 01:23:20.860
So it is harder.

01:23:20.860 --> 01:23:21.480
Yes, question?

01:23:21.480 --> 01:23:25.316
AUDIENCE: What do you do about
the fact that a lot of people

01:23:25.316 --> 01:23:27.842
will just ignore the
solution sets?

01:23:27.842 --> 01:23:31.050
Or do you just consider
that their problem?

01:23:31.050 --> 01:23:33.300
PROFESSOR: So the question is,
what do I do about people who

01:23:33.300 --> 01:23:34.540
just ignore the solution sets?

01:23:34.540 --> 01:23:35.930
Because a lot of students
do that.

01:23:35.930 --> 01:23:40.200
Yeah, partly I consider
it their problem.

01:23:40.200 --> 01:23:43.420
Because look, that's there
for them to learn.

01:23:43.420 --> 01:23:46.640
But partly, to the extent that
they're ignoring the solution

01:23:46.640 --> 01:23:49.140
set because they only cared
about the grade.

01:23:49.140 --> 01:23:50.970
So one cause of that
is they really only

01:23:50.970 --> 01:23:51.760
care about the grade.

01:23:51.760 --> 01:23:54.050
So they just want to wait for
the grader to give them back

01:23:54.050 --> 01:23:57.440
their solutions, their problem
set with a mark on it.

01:23:57.440 --> 01:23:59.060
And they don't care what's
right and wrong.

01:23:59.060 --> 01:24:01.390
That, I think, partly, is our
responsibility that we've

01:24:01.390 --> 01:24:04.620
chosen boring problems.

01:24:04.620 --> 01:24:08.300
So to fix that, I think, one
of the key areas is to use

01:24:08.300 --> 01:24:10.650
more of the Bloom's Taxonomy and
make interesting problems.

01:24:10.650 --> 01:24:14.420
And the flip side is to
deemphasize the grading.

01:24:14.420 --> 01:24:17.770
So actually, I like the
PDF scale on homework.

01:24:17.770 --> 01:24:20.180
I think we are too
micromanaging, generally,

01:24:20.180 --> 01:24:22.150
about homework, you know,
grading it on a percentage

01:24:22.150 --> 01:24:26.070
scale, on A, B, C, D. P,
you did a reasonable.

01:24:26.070 --> 01:24:29.290
And D, you blew it off.

01:24:29.290 --> 01:24:30.810
You did something but
it was a joke.

01:24:30.810 --> 01:24:32.660
And F, you didn't turn it in.

01:24:32.660 --> 01:24:35.910
I think that scale puts the
right emphasis on the grading.

01:24:35.910 --> 01:24:38.590
Look, we just want you to
do the thing and try it.

01:24:38.590 --> 01:24:42.160
And if the problems are
interesting that allows people

01:24:42.160 --> 01:24:43.840
to actually get involved
in it.

01:24:43.840 --> 01:24:47.010
So there's lots of studies that
show that if you reward

01:24:47.010 --> 01:24:49.570
people for things they
already enjoy--

01:24:49.570 --> 01:24:51.580
so you start paying them more
for doing things they really

01:24:51.580 --> 01:24:54.551
like-- they actually start
liking them less.

01:24:54.551 --> 01:24:57.250
So I'll talk about that as one
of the political barriers to

01:24:57.250 --> 01:24:58.080
educational change.

01:24:58.080 --> 01:25:01.550
Because that's completely
against the conventional

01:25:01.550 --> 01:25:04.210
psychology of this society,
where everything has to be

01:25:04.210 --> 01:25:06.280
rewarded, merit-based pay
and this and that.

01:25:06.280 --> 01:25:07.560
So how do you go against that?

01:25:07.560 --> 01:25:08.770
It's quite difficult.

01:25:08.770 --> 01:25:11.550
But one way, in general, in
those problem sets is to

01:25:11.550 --> 01:25:13.030
deemphasize the grading.

01:25:13.030 --> 01:25:14.140
Related method--

01:25:14.140 --> 01:25:16.730
which I haven't tried yet
but I'm planning to--

01:25:16.730 --> 01:25:19.540
is reading memos on
the solution set.

01:25:19.540 --> 01:25:21.720
So I talked about reading
memos before.

01:25:21.720 --> 01:25:24.250
And maybe one of you will try
it before me and can tell me

01:25:24.250 --> 01:25:24.970
how it works.

01:25:24.970 --> 01:25:25.710
A reading memo is--

01:25:25.710 --> 01:25:28.710
I talked about-- where you
have the students take a

01:25:28.710 --> 01:25:31.690
reading and mark--
either online or

01:25:31.690 --> 01:25:32.980
on a piece of paper--

01:25:32.980 --> 01:25:35.360
things that were confusing or
things that were interesting

01:25:35.360 --> 01:25:37.610
and things they noticed.

01:25:37.610 --> 01:25:39.980
Well, you can do that with
the solution set too.

01:25:39.980 --> 01:25:44.870
You say, OK, your assignment,
homework 3A is to look at the

01:25:44.870 --> 01:25:47.230
solution set for homework
two and mark

01:25:47.230 --> 01:25:48.890
anything that's confusing.

01:25:48.890 --> 01:25:51.200
So that forces people to
read the solution set.

01:25:51.200 --> 01:25:53.615
And often what you'll find is
that they'll find mistakes in

01:25:53.615 --> 01:25:56.210
the solution set, which is good
to know because you can

01:25:56.210 --> 01:25:57.120
correct them right away.

01:25:57.120 --> 01:26:01.028
But you'll see what parts are
confusing to students or not.

01:26:01.028 --> 01:26:02.880
Did that help answer
your question?

01:26:02.880 --> 01:26:05.290
Great.

01:26:05.290 --> 01:26:07.480
Do I ever asked Wheeler's
question explicitly?

01:26:07.480 --> 01:26:09.140
Yes, sometimes.

01:26:09.140 --> 01:26:11.610
I should do it more in
class in lecture.

01:26:11.610 --> 01:26:13.380
But I do it a lot to myself.

01:26:13.380 --> 01:26:15.090
Whenever I solve a problem
I think oh,

01:26:15.090 --> 01:26:16.590
what was the key idea?

01:26:16.590 --> 01:26:20.440
And then once I see the key idea
happen many times I think

01:26:20.440 --> 01:26:21.830
oh, that's a very key idea.

01:26:21.830 --> 01:26:24.190
That should be taught
explicitly in class.

01:26:24.190 --> 01:26:25.190
So I do that.

01:26:25.190 --> 01:26:27.100
And I'm going to talk about
that principle of course

01:26:27.100 --> 01:26:29.990
design today, basically
organizing courses around

01:26:29.990 --> 01:26:32.980
large themes and principles,
which is one of the main

01:26:32.980 --> 01:26:35.850
[? cures. ?]

01:26:35.850 --> 01:26:39.730
OK, so what's wrong with
tension as a force?

01:26:39.730 --> 01:26:43.380
How far should I go
down the taxonomy?

01:26:43.380 --> 01:26:46.290
Basically, where in the
course should I be?

01:26:46.290 --> 01:26:49.150
Really low in the taxonomy
early and higher later?

01:26:49.150 --> 01:26:50.650
Well, I talked about that
a bit last time.

01:26:50.650 --> 01:26:52.560
The fractal picture
is not bad.

01:26:52.560 --> 01:26:56.600
So yeah, you have a few
low-level examples and

01:26:56.600 --> 01:26:57.530
higher-level examples.

01:26:57.530 --> 01:26:59.560
But you do that throughout
the course.

01:26:59.560 --> 01:27:01.200
So you don't wait until the end
of the course to get the

01:27:01.200 --> 01:27:05.120
reward of the really interesting
problems.

01:27:05.120 --> 01:27:08.350
And then related to that, what
about exams and homework?

01:27:08.350 --> 01:27:10.500
Should they be the same
or different?

01:27:10.500 --> 01:27:14.380
My view is they should be the
same given the constraint that

01:27:14.380 --> 01:27:16.200
maybe the exam is done
in a shorter time.

01:27:16.200 --> 01:27:17.460
So if anything, the
exam should be

01:27:17.460 --> 01:27:19.190
easier than the homework.

01:27:19.190 --> 01:27:21.010
Generally, homework people
will spend six

01:27:21.010 --> 01:27:23.070
or seven hours on.

01:27:23.070 --> 01:27:25.160
When I was an undergraduate
we had take-home exams.

01:27:25.160 --> 01:27:26.680
And we would spend
24 hours on them.

01:27:26.680 --> 01:27:27.900
You pick them up, you
signed it out.

01:27:27.900 --> 01:27:29.070
You'd turned it in
in 24 hours.

01:27:29.070 --> 01:27:30.200
So that was misery.

01:27:30.200 --> 01:27:31.680
And it was interesting.

01:27:31.680 --> 01:27:32.430
You learnt a lot.

01:27:32.430 --> 01:27:34.670
But it was kind of miserable
because it just wiped out a

01:27:34.670 --> 01:27:36.960
whole day from your quarter.

01:27:36.960 --> 01:27:38.285
And you had that for
four classes.

01:27:38.285 --> 01:27:40.950
So four days from your quarter
were just gone.

01:27:40.950 --> 01:27:44.220
So generally, exams are three
hours, maybe two hours.

01:27:44.220 --> 01:27:46.430
And so that's much less time
than a homework set.

01:27:46.430 --> 01:27:48.600
So if anything, exams
should be easier,

01:27:48.600 --> 01:27:49.860
definitely not harder.

01:27:49.860 --> 01:27:53.210
Student loath when the exam does
different things than the

01:27:53.210 --> 01:27:54.700
problem sets.

01:27:54.700 --> 01:27:56.850
And that is a general principle
of course design,

01:27:56.850 --> 01:27:58.720
that if you want to prepare
them for being able to do

01:27:58.720 --> 01:28:00.580
stuff-- for example
on the exam--

01:28:00.580 --> 01:28:02.110
you have to prepare
them with things.

01:28:02.110 --> 01:28:04.560
You have to "teach to the test."
That's actually good.

01:28:04.560 --> 01:28:06.940
You want your homeworks
to be like the exam.

01:28:06.940 --> 01:28:09.580
And that's fine if
the test is good.

01:28:09.580 --> 01:28:12.770
If the test tests real-world,
interesting skills sure, then

01:28:12.770 --> 01:28:14.610
it's fine to teach the test
because they'll come out being

01:28:14.610 --> 01:28:16.290
able to do that, no problem.

01:28:16.290 --> 01:28:18.580
So the exam and homework-- as
a rough rule of function--

01:28:18.580 --> 01:28:19.770
will be pretty much the same.

01:28:19.770 --> 01:28:21.790
Or if anything, the exam
should be easier.

01:28:32.880 --> 01:28:35.150
Oh yeah, the first time
you teach a class.

01:28:35.150 --> 01:28:38.000
So all this Bloom's Taxonomy
and designing questions, it

01:28:38.000 --> 01:28:38.860
takes a long time.

01:28:38.860 --> 01:28:40.580
And it's really hard to
make good questions.

01:28:40.580 --> 01:28:43.040
It's easy to make define
XYZ questions.

01:28:43.040 --> 01:28:44.710
But what about the higher-level
questions?

01:28:44.710 --> 01:28:47.620
What do you do to mitigate
that problem of a

01:28:47.620 --> 01:28:49.550
huge amount of time?

01:28:49.550 --> 01:28:53.850
Well, one of the cures is to
cooperate with other teachers.

01:28:53.850 --> 01:28:55.870
So you steal their
good problems.

01:28:55.870 --> 01:28:58.830
So I gave you the T.S. Eliot
saying before, that talent

01:28:58.830 --> 01:29:00.850
invents and genius steals.

01:29:00.850 --> 01:29:03.070
So be a genius.

01:29:03.070 --> 01:29:05.010
Whenever you see a good
problem just use it.

01:29:05.010 --> 01:29:07.590
And whenever someone wants
a good problem, if you

01:29:07.590 --> 01:29:09.050
have one, share it.

01:29:09.050 --> 01:29:11.830
And now, should you guard
your problems?

01:29:11.830 --> 01:29:17.030
I think those days of guarding
problems are gone.

01:29:17.030 --> 01:29:20.840
They've gone by because of
things like OpenCourseWare,

01:29:20.840 --> 01:29:22.610
putting problem sets online.

01:29:22.610 --> 01:29:24.980
It's just not possible anymore
to guard problems.

01:29:24.980 --> 01:29:26.500
I'm not sure it was
ever a good idea.

01:29:26.500 --> 01:29:28.290
But now it's not
even practical.

01:29:28.290 --> 01:29:32.940
So everything is online, all
from the previous year.

01:29:32.940 --> 01:29:34.760
So the problems can't
be guarded.

01:29:34.760 --> 01:29:37.480
And it's not practical to make
up a whole set of new good

01:29:37.480 --> 01:29:38.830
problems for the next year.

01:29:38.830 --> 01:29:40.730
You'll never sleep.

01:29:40.730 --> 01:29:45.050
So I just trust the students not
to cheat by looking at the

01:29:45.050 --> 01:29:46.280
old solution sets.

01:29:46.280 --> 01:29:51.550
And if you're grading, that's
yet another reason to minimize

01:29:51.550 --> 01:29:53.350
how strict the grading is.

01:29:53.350 --> 01:29:55.740
So if the grading is really,
just that they make an effort

01:29:55.740 --> 01:29:58.410
and try to learn something,
then there's no benefit to

01:29:58.410 --> 01:30:01.080
cheating and looking at
the old solution sets.

01:30:01.080 --> 01:30:05.220
So you actually make the
incentive structure so that

01:30:05.220 --> 01:30:06.280
they don't need to do all that.

01:30:06.280 --> 01:30:06.700
Question?

01:30:06.700 --> 01:30:08.197
AUDIENCE: Do you have to change
your problem to a

01:30:08.197 --> 01:30:11.357
certain extent in terms
of plagiarism?

01:30:14.145 --> 01:30:16.000
PROFESSOR: So the question is,
do I have to change the

01:30:16.000 --> 01:30:18.560
problems to a certain extent
to avoid plagiarism?

01:30:18.560 --> 01:30:19.770
I don't even care.

01:30:19.770 --> 01:30:20.980
I don't even change them.

01:30:20.980 --> 01:30:24.060
I think, again, it's sort of
what Adrian has said, is it

01:30:24.060 --> 01:30:25.330
their problem if they do it?

01:30:25.330 --> 01:30:27.240
And to some extent it
is their problem.

01:30:27.240 --> 01:30:30.390
If they're going to cheat and
look at the old solution set

01:30:30.390 --> 01:30:33.020
and not acknowledge it.

01:30:33.020 --> 01:30:34.970
There's only so much
you can do.

01:30:34.970 --> 01:30:38.550
And you then get in an
arms race with them.

01:30:38.550 --> 01:30:40.870
You change the problem
to some extent.

01:30:40.870 --> 01:30:43.370
But then someone
else makes it.

01:30:43.370 --> 01:30:44.670
So they can always
subvert that.

01:30:44.670 --> 01:30:46.700
One person can solve the new
problem and give it to

01:30:46.700 --> 01:30:47.800
everybody else.

01:30:47.800 --> 01:30:52.030
So you have no hope of actually
winning that war,

01:30:52.030 --> 01:30:54.470
even if it were a moral
war to try to win.

01:30:54.470 --> 01:30:55.610
So I don't even change them.

01:30:55.610 --> 01:30:57.500
And I say look, just
acknowledge, just like you

01:30:57.500 --> 01:30:59.620
would in science.

01:30:59.620 --> 01:31:03.230
I think it's Larry Lessig,
the copyright scholar,

01:31:03.230 --> 01:31:04.210
professor of law.

01:31:04.210 --> 01:31:04.980
He used to be at Harvard.

01:31:04.980 --> 01:31:06.170
Now it's Stanford.

01:31:06.170 --> 01:31:10.640
He founded Creative Commons
and various fantastic

01:31:10.640 --> 01:31:11.410
copyright projects.

01:31:11.410 --> 01:31:15.650
So he said, well, there's a
couple ways to get-- not

01:31:15.650 --> 01:31:16.560
compliance--

01:31:16.560 --> 01:31:17.460
people to do things.

01:31:17.460 --> 01:31:20.360
One is you can do it
through rules.

01:31:20.360 --> 01:31:21.580
For example, this is illegal.

01:31:21.580 --> 01:31:23.390
You just can't do this.

01:31:23.390 --> 01:31:24.657
We'll punish you
if you do this.

01:31:24.657 --> 01:31:26.360
The other one is through norm.

01:31:26.360 --> 01:31:28.120
So this is just not done.

01:31:28.120 --> 01:31:30.690
In our community we just don't
do things like that.

01:31:30.690 --> 01:31:33.560
And generally, this kind
of-- not exhortation--

01:31:33.560 --> 01:31:38.940
but push works much better
than the punishment kind.

01:31:38.940 --> 01:31:44.260
So I just tell them, look, in
science when you grow up and

01:31:44.260 --> 01:31:48.300
become a scientist of course you
acknowledge your peers and

01:31:48.300 --> 01:31:49.140
people you learn from.

01:31:49.140 --> 01:31:50.640
Because that's just polite.

01:31:50.640 --> 01:31:51.910
It's just how we are.

01:31:51.910 --> 01:31:52.830
We say, please.

01:31:52.830 --> 01:31:55.090
We don't say gimme,
gimme, gimme.

01:31:55.090 --> 01:31:56.860
I'm working on teaching my
daughter that right now.

01:31:56.860 --> 01:31:59.490
She says, daddy read.

01:31:59.490 --> 01:32:00.020
Daddy read.

01:32:00.020 --> 01:32:00.780
Mommy read.

01:32:00.780 --> 01:32:01.600
Elsa read.

01:32:01.600 --> 01:32:02.990
I'm like OK, I'm fine
with the Elsa read.

01:32:02.990 --> 01:32:04.530
But daddy read, mommy
read, that's nice.

01:32:04.530 --> 01:32:05.320
And we love reading.

01:32:05.320 --> 01:32:07.660
But how do you ask?

01:32:07.660 --> 01:32:10.410
And now she says mommy read
please, daddy read please.

01:32:10.410 --> 01:32:13.380
And so it's the start.

01:32:13.380 --> 01:32:15.170
So people already learnt
that from young.

01:32:15.170 --> 01:32:16.380
So you can tap into that.

01:32:16.380 --> 01:32:19.370
Look, how do you act as a
member of the community?

01:32:19.370 --> 01:32:20.320
We're social animals.

01:32:20.320 --> 01:32:21.320
So you don't have
to put too much

01:32:21.320 --> 01:32:22.660
pressure in that direction.

01:32:22.660 --> 01:32:24.490
Whereas if you try to do it
through a punishment you have

01:32:24.490 --> 01:32:26.760
to work much harder.

01:32:26.760 --> 01:32:29.030
The punishment one--

01:32:29.030 --> 01:32:29.650
underneath--

01:32:29.650 --> 01:32:32.670
has the idea that we don't
trust the students.

01:32:32.670 --> 01:32:32.870
Right?

01:32:32.870 --> 01:32:36.250
And in that way it's common with
changing the numbers on

01:32:36.250 --> 01:32:38.420
the problems set.

01:32:38.420 --> 01:32:41.130
It's that we don't trust you so
we're changing the numbers.

01:32:41.130 --> 01:32:45.550
So I try to avoid those things
as much as possible and try to

01:32:45.550 --> 01:32:47.170
go more towards this.

01:32:47.170 --> 01:32:47.620
Yes?

01:32:47.620 --> 01:32:50.987
AUDIENCE: Has anyone tried
to have problem

01:32:50.987 --> 01:32:52.430
sets without solutions?

01:32:52.430 --> 01:32:56.278
So then there's no grading.

01:32:56.278 --> 01:32:59.660
And then the problem sets
are just for practicing.

01:32:59.660 --> 01:33:03.090
PROFESSOR: Yeah, have problem
sets for practice with no

01:33:03.090 --> 01:33:05.600
solutions or no grading
on the problem sets?

01:33:05.600 --> 01:33:06.410
Have people tried that?

01:33:06.410 --> 01:33:08.020
So there's actually
whole educational

01:33:08.020 --> 01:33:09.540
systems based on that.

01:33:09.540 --> 01:33:12.580
Not so much in America, but
in England, the Oxford and

01:33:12.580 --> 01:33:14.520
Cambridge tutorial system.

01:33:14.520 --> 01:33:16.030
You're given problems
to work on.

01:33:16.030 --> 01:33:19.100
So I was on both sides
of that system.

01:33:19.100 --> 01:33:21.790
You're given problems to
work with your tutor.

01:33:21.790 --> 01:33:23.650
And they're not graded.

01:33:23.650 --> 01:33:25.370
I mean, your tutor helps
you make sure that

01:33:25.370 --> 01:33:26.640
you can do the problems.

01:33:26.640 --> 01:33:29.380
But everything that's graded
happens at the end.

01:33:29.380 --> 01:33:31.240
Well, when I was an
undergraduate it happened at

01:33:31.240 --> 01:33:32.640
the end of your entire degree.

01:33:32.640 --> 01:33:36.050
There was eight three-hour
exams that counted for

01:33:36.050 --> 01:33:36.460
everything.

01:33:36.460 --> 01:33:37.920
And nothing else counted.

01:33:37.920 --> 01:33:40.550
So it had some craziness.

01:33:40.550 --> 01:33:42.960
That time at the end was
pretty stressful.

01:33:42.960 --> 01:33:46.610
But before that your tutor
was actually your friend.

01:33:46.610 --> 01:33:48.570
And your tutor wasn't the
person doing the exams.

01:33:48.570 --> 01:33:51.190
So you would do problems because
you wanted to learn

01:33:51.190 --> 01:33:53.070
and your tutor would help you
so that you would do well on

01:33:53.070 --> 01:33:54.900
the exam that other people
were setting.

01:33:54.900 --> 01:33:58.476
So you had a nice alliance
with your tutor.

01:33:58.476 --> 01:34:00.284
AUDIENCE: Does that work well?

01:34:03.105 --> 01:34:04.750
PROFESSOR: I would say
it works well.

01:34:04.750 --> 01:34:07.190
At MIT it would work great.

01:34:07.190 --> 01:34:08.220
Given [INAUDIBLE]

01:34:08.220 --> 01:34:10.880
that people are too
overloaded.

01:34:10.880 --> 01:34:13.430
And they would say, oh well, if
there's not going to be any

01:34:13.430 --> 01:34:15.700
grading at all, I don't have
to do anything, while I'd

01:34:15.700 --> 01:34:17.230
really like to do this
problem set.

01:34:17.230 --> 01:34:19.590
But I have four other classes
that are making me work 20

01:34:19.590 --> 01:34:20.180
hours a week.

01:34:20.180 --> 01:34:21.630
And I don't have any time.

01:34:21.630 --> 01:34:23.580
So then because of the
other pressures

01:34:23.580 --> 01:34:24.290
they might fall away.

01:34:24.290 --> 01:34:25.300
But they would like to do it.

01:34:25.300 --> 01:34:28.510
So that's why I compromise by
just saying, you have to do

01:34:28.510 --> 01:34:29.940
the thing and make an effort.

01:34:29.940 --> 01:34:32.500
And then I trust that once they
start trying it they'll

01:34:32.500 --> 01:34:35.700
enjoy doing it.

01:34:35.700 --> 01:34:38.490
So I tried to make it as light
as I think you can get away

01:34:38.490 --> 01:34:40.020
with at MIT, given the
pressures from

01:34:40.020 --> 01:34:41.410
all the other teachers.

01:34:41.410 --> 01:34:44.230
But in the ideal world I think
that's what we would do here.

01:34:44.230 --> 01:34:45.195
There wouldn't be
that pressure.

01:34:45.195 --> 01:34:47.760
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]?

01:34:47.760 --> 01:34:51.880
PROFESSOR: Yeah, in Oxford and
Cambridge it works very well,

01:34:51.880 --> 01:34:53.440
provided you have
a good tutor.

01:34:53.440 --> 01:34:57.790
And there's many students who
are there just because it's a

01:34:57.790 --> 01:35:00.200
thing to do, to go to Oxford
and Cambridge.

01:35:00.200 --> 01:35:02.780
But if you factor out those
students who are just there

01:35:02.780 --> 01:35:06.040
for the stamp of the place,
for the other students it

01:35:06.040 --> 01:35:07.305
works fantastically well.

01:35:07.305 --> 01:35:11.210
I mean, the tutorials are
a great discussion time.

01:35:11.210 --> 01:35:14.460
